# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: formal-methods
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:formal-methods/abstract-interpretation] In computer science, **abstract interpretation** is a theory of sound approximation of the semantics of computer programs, based on monotonic functions over ordered sets, especially lattices.
[src:formal-methods/abstract-interpretation] It can be viewed as a partial execution of a computer program which gains information about its semantics (e.g., control-flow, data-flow) without performing all the calculations.
[src:formal-methods/abstract-interpretation] Abstract interpretation was formalized by the French computer scientist working couple Patrick Cousot and Radhia Cousot in the late 1970s.
[src:formal-methods/abstract-interpretation] This section illustrates abstract interpretation by means of real-world, non-computing examples.
[src:formal-methods/abstract-interpretation] Consider the people in a conference room.
[src:formal-methods/abstract-interpretation] Assume a unique identifier for each person in the room, like a social security number in the United States.
[src:formal-methods/abstract-interpretation] To prove that someone is not present, all one needs to do is see if their social security number is not on the list.
[src:formal-methods/abstract-interpretation] Since two different people cannot have the same number, it is possible to prove or disprove the presence of a participant simply by looking up their number.
[src:formal-methods/abstract-interpretation] However it is possible that only the names of attendees were registered.
[src:formal-methods/abstract-interpretation] If the name of a person is not found in the list, we may safely conclude that that person was not present; but if it is, we cannot conclude definitely without further inquiries, due to the possibility of homonyms (for example, two people named John Smith).
[src:formal-methods/abstract-interpretation] Note that this imprecise information will still be adequate for most purposes, because homonyms are rare in practice.
[src:formal-methods/abstract-interpretation] However, in all rigor, we cannot say for sure that somebody was present in the room; all we can say is that they were *possibly* here.
[src:formal-methods/abstract-interpretation] If the person we are looking up is a criminal, we will issue an *alarm*; but there is of course the possibility of issuing a *false alarm*.
[src:formal-methods/abstract-interpretation] Similar phenomena will occur in the analysis of programs.
[src:formal-methods/abstract-interpretation] If we are only interested in some specific information, say, "was there a person of age n in the room?", keeping a list of all names and dates of births is unnecessary.
[src:formal-methods/abstract-interpretation] We may safely and without loss of precision restrict ourselves to keeping a list of the participants' ages.
[src:formal-methods/abstract-interpretation] If this is already too much to handle, we might keep only the age of the youngest, m and oldest person, M .
[src:formal-methods/abstract-interpretation] If the question is about an age strictly lower than m or strictly higher than M , then we may safely respond that no such participant was present.
[src:formal-methods/abstract-interpretation] Otherwise, we may only be able to say that we do not know.
[src:formal-methods/abstract-interpretation] In the case of computing, concrete, precise information is in general not computable within finite time and memory (see Rice's theorem and the halting problem).
[src:formal-methods/abstract-interpretation] One crucial requirement is to add enough vagueness so as to make problems manageable while still retaining enough precision for answering the important questions (such as "might the program crash?").
[src:formal-methods/abstract-interpretation] Given a programming or specification language, abstract interpretation consists of giving several semantics linked by relations of abstraction.
[src:formal-methods/abstract-interpretation] A semantics is a mathematical characterization of a possible behavior of the program.
[src:formal-methods/abstract-interpretation] The most precise semantics, describing very closely the actual execution of the program, are called the *concrete semantics*.
[src:formal-methods/abstract-interpretation] More abstract semantics are then derived; for instance, one may consider only the set of reachable states in the executions (which amounts to considering the last states in finite traces).
[src:formal-methods/abstract-interpretation] The goal of static analysis is to derive a computable semantic interpretation at some point.
[src:formal-methods/abstract-interpretation] For instance, one may choose to represent the state of a program manipulating integer variables by forgetting the actual values of the variables and only keeping their signs (+, − or 0).
[src:formal-methods/abstract-interpretation] For some elementary operations, such as multiplication, such an abstraction does not lose any precision: to get the sign of a product, it is sufficient to know the sign of the operands.
[src:formal-methods/abstract-interpretation] For some other operations, the abstraction may lose precision: for instance, it is impossible to know the sign of a sum whose operands are respectively positive and negative.
[src:formal-methods/abstract-interpretation] Sometimes a loss of precision is necessary to make the semantics decidable (see Rice's theorem and the halting problem).
[src:formal-methods/abstract-interpretation] In general, there is a compromise to be made between the precision of the analysis and its decidability (computability), or tractability (computational cost).
[src:formal-methods/abstract-interpretation] In practice the abstractions that are defined are tailored to both the program properties one desires to analyze, and to the set of target programs.
[src:formal-methods/abstract-interpretation] The first large scale automated analysis of computer programs with abstract interpretation was motivated by the accident that resulted in the destruction of the first flight of the Ariane 5 rocket in 1996.
[src:formal-methods/abstract-interpretation] Let L be an ordered set, called *concrete set*, and let $L'$ be another ordered set, called *abstract set*.
[src:formal-methods/abstract-interpretation] These two sets are related to each other by defining total functions that map elements from one to the other.
[src:formal-methods/abstract-interpretation] A function $\alpha$ is called an *abstraction function* if it maps an element x in the concrete set L to an element $\alpha (x)$ in the abstract set $L'$ .
[src:formal-methods/abstract-interpretation] That is, element $\alpha (x)$ in $L'$ is the *abstraction* of x in L .
[src:formal-methods/abstract-interpretation] A function $\gamma$ is called a *concretization function* if it maps an element $x'$ in the abstract set $L'$ to an element $\gamma (x')$ in the concrete set L .
[src:formal-methods/abstract-interpretation] That is, element $\gamma (x')$ in L is a *concretization* of $x'$ in $L'$ .
[src:formal-methods/abstract-interpretation] The concrete semantics f is a monotonic function from $L_{1}$ to $L_{2}$ .
[src:formal-methods/abstract-interpretation] Program semantics are generally described using fixed points in the presence of loops or recursive procedures.
[src:formal-methods/abstract-interpretation] Suppose that L is a complete lattice and let f be a monotonic function from L into L .
[src:formal-methods/abstract-interpretation] Then, any $x'$ such that $f(x')\leq x'$ is an abstraction of the least fixed-point of f , which exists, according to the Knaster–Tarski theorem.
[src:formal-methods/abstract-interpretation] The difficulty is now to obtain such an $x'$ .
[src:formal-methods/abstract-interpretation] In some cases, it is possible to define abstractions using Galois connections $(\alpha ,\gamma )$ where $\alpha$ is from L to $L'$ and $\gamma$ is from $L'$ to L .
[src:formal-methods/abstract-interpretation] This supposes the existence of best abstractions, which is not necessarily the case.
[src:formal-methods/abstract-interpretation] For instance, if we abstract sets of couples $(x,y)$ of real numbers by enclosing convex polyhedra, there is no optimal abstraction to the disc defined by $x^{2}+y^{2}\leq 1$ .
[src:formal-methods/abstract-interpretation] One can assign to each variable x available at a given program point an interval $[L_{x},H_{x}]$ .
[src:formal-methods/abstract-interpretation] A state assigning the value $v(x)$ to variable x will be a concretization of these intervals if, for all x , we have $v(x)\in [L_{x},H_{x}]$ .
[src:formal-methods/abstract-interpretation] More complex formulas can be derived for multiplication, division, etc., yielding so-called interval arithmetics.
[src:formal-methods/abstract-interpretation] With reasonable arithmetic types, the result for z should be zero.
[src:formal-methods/abstract-interpretation] But if we do interval arithmetic starting from x in [0, 1], one gets z in [−1, +1].
[src:formal-methods/abstract-interpretation] While each of the operations taken individually was exactly abstracted, their composition isn't.
[src:formal-methods/abstract-interpretation] The problem is evident: we did not keep track of the equality relationship between x and y; actually, this domain of intervals does not take into account any relationships between variables, and is thus a *non-relational domain*.
[src:formal-methods/abstract-interpretation] Non-relational domains tend to be fast and simple to implement, but imprecise.
[src:formal-methods/abstract-interpretation] and combinations thereof (such as the reduced product, cf. right picture).
[src:formal-methods/abstract-interpretation] When one chooses an abstract domain, one typically has to strike a balance between keeping fine-grained relationships, and high computational costs.
[src:formal-methods/abstract-interpretation] There are several abstract domains suitable for various analyses of such variables.
[src:formal-methods/abstract-interpretation] The *bitfield domain* treats each bit in a machine word separately, i.e., a word of width *n* is treated as an array of *n* abstract values.
[src:formal-methods/abstract-interpretation] Further domains include the *signed interval domain* and the *unsigned interval domain*.
[src:formal-methods/abstract-interpretation] All three of these domains support forwards and backwards abstract operators for common operations such as addition, shifts, xor, and multiplication.
[src:formal-methods/abstract-interpretation] These domains can be combined using the reduced product.
[src:formal-methods/design-by-contract] It prescribes that software designers should define formal, precise and verifiable interface specifications for software components, which extend the ordinary definition of abstract data types with preconditions, postconditions and invariants.
[src:formal-methods/design-by-contract] These specifications are referred to as "contracts", in accordance with a conceptual metaphor with the conditions and obligations of business contracts.
[src:formal-methods/design-by-contract] The DbC approach assumes all *client components* that invoke an operation on a *server component* will meet the preconditions specified as required for that operation.
[src:formal-methods/design-by-contract] The term was coined by Bertrand Meyer in connection with his design of the Eiffel programming language and first described in various articles starting in 1986 and the two successive editions (1988, 1997) of his book *Object-Oriented Software Construction*.
[src:formal-methods/design-by-contract] Eiffel Software applied for trademark registration for *Design by Contract* in December 2003, and it was granted in December 2004.
[src:formal-methods/design-by-contract] The current owner of this trademark is Eiffel Software.
[src:formal-methods/design-by-contract] Design by contract has its roots in work on formal verification, formal specification and Hoare logic.
[src:formal-methods/design-by-contract] The central idea of DbC is a metaphor on how elements of a software system collaborate with each other on the basis of mutual *obligations* and *benefits*.
[src:formal-methods/design-by-contract] The contract is semantically equivalent to a Hoare triple which formalises the obligations.
[src:formal-methods/design-by-contract] Many programming languages have facilities to make assertions like these.
[src:formal-methods/design-by-contract] However, DbC considers these contracts to be so crucial to software correctness that they should be part of the design process.
[src:formal-methods/design-by-contract] In effect, DbC advocates writing the assertions first.
[src:formal-methods/design-by-contract] Contracts can be written by code comments, enforced by a test suite, or both, even if there is no special language support for contracts.
[src:formal-methods/design-by-contract] Subclasses in an inheritance hierarchy are allowed to weaken preconditions (but not strengthen them) and strengthen postconditions and invariants (but not weaken them).
[src:formal-methods/design-by-contract] These rules approximate behavioural subtyping.
[src:formal-methods/design-by-contract] All class relationships are between client classes and supplier classes.
[src:formal-methods/design-by-contract] A client class is obliged to make calls to supplier features where the resulting state of the supplier is not violated by the client call.
[src:formal-methods/design-by-contract] Subsequently, the supplier is obliged to provide a return state and data that does not violate the state requirements of the client.
[src:formal-methods/design-by-contract] For instance, a supplier data buffer may require that data is present in the buffer when a delete feature is called.
[src:formal-methods/design-by-contract] Subsequently, the supplier guarantees to the client that when a delete feature finishes its work, the data item will, indeed, be deleted from the buffer.
[src:formal-methods/design-by-contract] Other design contracts are concepts of class invariant.
[src:formal-methods/design-by-contract] The class invariant guarantees (for the local class) that the state of the class will be maintained within specified tolerances at the end of each feature execution.
[src:formal-methods/design-by-contract] When using contracts, a supplier will verify that the contract conditions are satisfied—a practice known as offensive programming—the general idea being that code should "fail hard", with contract verification being the safety net.
[src:formal-methods/design-by-contract] DbC's "fail hard" property simplifies the debugging of contract behavior, as the intended behaviour of each method is clearly specified.
[src:formal-methods/design-by-contract] This approach differs substantially from that of defensive programming, where the supplier is responsible for figuring out what to do when a precondition is broken.
[src:formal-methods/design-by-contract] More often than not, the supplier throws an exception to inform the client that the precondition has been broken, and in both cases—DbC and defensive programming alike—the client must figure out how to respond to that.
[src:formal-methods/design-by-contract] In such cases, DbC makes the supplier's job easier.
[src:formal-methods/design-by-contract] Design by contract can also facilitate code reuse, since the contract for each piece of code is fully documented.
[src:formal-methods/design-by-contract] The contracts for a module can be regarded as a form of software documentation for the behavior of that module.
[src:formal-methods/design-by-contract] Contract conditions should never be violated during execution of a bug-free program.
[src:formal-methods/design-by-contract] Contracts are therefore typically only checked in debug mode during software development.
[src:formal-methods/design-by-contract] Later at release, the contract checks are disabled to maximize performance.
[src:formal-methods/design-by-contract] In many programming languages, contracts are implemented with assert.
[src:formal-methods/design-by-contract] Asserts are by default compiled away in release mode in C/C++, and similarly deactivated in C# and Java.
[src:formal-methods/design-by-contract] Launching the Python interpreter with "-O" (for "optimize") as an argument will likewise cause the Python code generator to not emit any bytecode for asserts.
[src:formal-methods/design-by-contract] This effectively eliminates the run-time costs of asserts in production code—irrespective of the number and computational expense of asserts used in development—as no such instructions will be included in production by the compiler.
[src:formal-methods/design-by-contract] Design by contract does not replace regular testing strategies, such as unit testing, integration testing and system testing.
[src:formal-methods/design-by-contract] Rather, it complements external testing with internal self-tests that can be activated both for isolated tests and in production code during a test-phase.
[src:formal-methods/design-by-contract] The advantage of internal self-tests is that they can detect errors before they manifest themselves as invalid results observed by the client.
[src:formal-methods/design-by-contract] This leads to earlier and more specific error detection.
[src:formal-methods/design-by-contract] The use of assertions can be considered to be a form of test oracle, a way of testing the design by contract implementation.
[src:formal-methods/design-by-contract] Further, the standard method combination in the Common Lisp Object System has the method qualifiers `:before`, `:after` and `:around` that allow writing contracts as auxiliary methods, among other uses.
[src:formal-methods/formal-methods] In computer science, **formal methods** are mathematically rigorous techniques for the specification, development, analysis, and verification of software and hardware systems.
[src:formal-methods/formal-methods] The use of formal methods for software and hardware design is motivated by the expectation that, as in other engineering disciplines, performing appropriate mathematical analysis can contribute to the reliability and robustness of a design.
[src:formal-methods/formal-methods] Formal methods employ a variety of theoretical computer science fundamentals, including logic calculi, formal languages, automata theory, control theory, program semantics, type systems, and type theory.
[src:formal-methods/formal-methods] Formal methods can be applied at various points through the development process.
[src:formal-methods/formal-methods] Formal methods may be used to give a formal description of the system to be developed, at whatever level of detail desired.
[src:formal-methods/formal-methods] Further formal methods may depend on this specification to synthesize a program or to verify the correctness of a system.
[src:formal-methods/formal-methods] Alternatively, specification may be the only stage in which formal methods are used.
[src:formal-methods/formal-methods] By writing a specification, ambiguities in the informal requirements can be discovered and resolved.
[src:formal-methods/formal-methods] Additionally, engineers can use a formal specification as a reference to guide their development processes.
[src:formal-methods/formal-methods] The need for formal specification systems has been noted for years.
[src:formal-methods/formal-methods] In the ALGOL 58 report, John Backus presented a formal notation for describing programming language syntax, later named Backus normal form then renamed Backus–Naur form (BNF).
[src:formal-methods/formal-methods] Backus also wrote that a formal description of the meaning of syntactically valid ALGOL programs was not completed in time for inclusion in the report, stating that it "will be included in a subsequent paper." However, no paper describing the formal semantics was ever released.
[src:formal-methods/formal-methods] Program synthesis is the process of automatically creating a program that conforms to a specification.
[src:formal-methods/formal-methods] Deductive synthesis approaches rely on a complete formal specification of the program, whereas inductive approaches infer the specification from examples.
[src:formal-methods/formal-methods] Synthesizers perform a search over the space of possible programs to find a program consistent with the specification.
[src:formal-methods/formal-methods] Because of the size of this search space, developing efficient search algorithms is one of the major challenges in program synthesis.
[src:formal-methods/formal-methods] Formal verification is the use of software tools to prove properties of a formal specification, or to prove that a formal model of a system implementation satisfies its specification.
[src:formal-methods/formal-methods] Once a formal specification has been developed, the specification may be used as the basis for proving properties of the specification, and by inference, properties of the system implementation.
[src:formal-methods/formal-methods] Sign-off verification is the use of a formal verification tool that is highly trusted.
[src:formal-methods/formal-methods] Such a tool can replace traditional verification methods (the tool may even be certified).
[src:formal-methods/formal-methods] Sometimes, the motivation for proving the correctness of a system is not the obvious need for reassurance of the correctness of the system, but a desire to understand the system better.
[src:formal-methods/formal-methods] Consequently, some proofs of correctness are produced in the style of mathematical proof: handwritten (or typeset) using natural language, using a level of informality common to such proofs.
[src:formal-methods/formal-methods] A "good" proof is one that is readable and understandable by other human readers.
[src:formal-methods/formal-methods] Critics of such approaches point out that the ambiguity inherent in natural language allows errors to be undetected in such proofs; often, subtle errors can be present in the low-level details typically overlooked by such proofs.
[src:formal-methods/formal-methods] Additionally, the work involved in producing such a good proof requires a high level of mathematical sophistication and expertise.
[src:formal-methods/formal-methods] In contrast, there is increasing interest in producing proofs of correctness of such systems by automated means.
[src:formal-methods/formal-methods] Some automated theorem provers require guidance as to which properties are "interesting" enough to pursue, while others work without human intervention.
[src:formal-methods/formal-methods] Model checkers can quickly get bogged down in checking millions of uninteresting states if not given a sufficiently abstract model.
[src:formal-methods/formal-methods] Proponents of such systems argue that the results have greater mathematical certainty than human-produced proofs, since all the tedious details have been algorithmically verified.
[src:formal-methods/formal-methods] The training required to use such systems is also less than that required to produce good mathematical proofs by hand, making the techniques accessible to a wider variety of practitioners.
[src:formal-methods/formal-methods] Critics note that some of those systems are like oracles: they make a pronouncement of truth, yet give no explanation of that truth.
[src:formal-methods/formal-methods] There is also the problem of "verifying the verifier"; if the program that aids in the verification is itself unproven, there may be reason to doubt the soundness of the produced results.
[src:formal-methods/formal-methods] Some modern model checking tools produce a "proof log" detailing each step in their proof, making it possible to perform, given suitable tools, independent verification.
[src:formal-methods/formal-methods] The main feature of the abstract interpretation approach is that it provides a sound analysis, i.e. no false negatives are returned.
[src:formal-methods/formal-methods] Moreover, it is efficiently scalable, by tuning the abstract domain representing the property to be analyzed, and by applying widening operators to get fast convergence.
[src:formal-methods/formal-methods] Formal methods includes a number of different techniques.
[src:formal-methods/formal-methods] The design of a computing system can be expressed using a specification language, which is a formal language that includes a proof system.
[src:formal-methods/formal-methods] Using this proof system, formal verification tools can reason about the specification and establish that a system adheres to the specification.
[src:formal-methods/formal-methods] A binary decision diagram is a data structure that represents a Boolean function.
[src:formal-methods/formal-methods] If a Boolean formula ${\mathcal {P}}$ expresses that an execution of a program conforms to the specification, a binary decision diagram can be used to determine if ${\mathcal {P}}$ is a tautology; that is, it always evaluates to TRUE.
[src:formal-methods/formal-methods] If this is the case, then the program always conforms to the specification.
[src:formal-methods/formal-methods] A SAT solver is a program that can solve the Boolean satisfiability problem, the problem of finding an assignment of variables that makes a given propositional formula evaluate to true.
[src:formal-methods/formal-methods] If a Boolean formula ${\mathcal {P}}$ expresses that a specific execution of a program conforms to the specification, then determining that $\neg {\mathcal {P}}$ is unsatisfiable is equivalent to determining that all executions conform to the specification.
[src:formal-methods/formal-methods] SAT solvers are often used in bounded model checking, but can also be used in unbounded model checking.
[src:formal-methods/formal-methods] Formal methods are applied in different areas of hardware and software, including routers, Ethernet switches, routing protocols, security applications, and operating system microkernels such as seL4.
[src:formal-methods/formal-methods] There are several examples in which they have been used to verify the functionality of the hardware and software used in data centres.
[src:formal-methods/formal-methods] IBM used ACL2, a theorem prover, in the AMD x86 processor development process.
[src:formal-methods/formal-methods] Intel uses such methods to verify its hardware and firmware (permanent software programmed into a read-only memory).
[src:formal-methods/formal-methods] Dansk Datamatik Center used formal methods in the 1980s to develop a compiler system for the Ada programming language that went on to become a long-lived commercial product.
[src:formal-methods/formal-methods] There are several other projects of NASA in which formal methods are applied, such as Next Generation Air Transportation System, Unmanned Aircraft System integration in National Airspace System, and Airborne Coordinated Conflict Resolution and Detection (ACCoRD).
[src:formal-methods/formal-methods] B-Method with Atelier B, is used to develop safety automatisms for the various subways installed throughout the world by Alstom and Siemens, and also for Common Criteria certification and the development of system models by ATMEL and STMicroelectronics.
[src:formal-methods/formal-methods] Formal verification has been frequently used in hardware by most of the well-known hardware vendors, such as IBM, Intel, and AMD.
[src:formal-methods/formal-methods] Similarly, IBM has used formal methods in the verification of power gates, registers, and functional verification of the IBM Power7 microprocessor.
[src:formal-methods/formal-methods] In software development, formal methods are mathematical approaches to solving software (and hardware) problems at the requirements, specification, and design levels.
[src:formal-methods/formal-methods] Formal methods are most likely to be applied to safety-critical or security-critical software and systems, such as avionics software.
[src:formal-methods/formal-methods] Software safety assurance standards, such as DO-178C allows the usage of formal methods through supplementation, and Common Criteria mandates formal methods at the highest levels of categorization.
[src:formal-methods/formal-methods] For sequential software, examples of formal methods include the B-Method, the specification languages used in automated theorem proving, RAISE, and the Z notation.
[src:formal-methods/formal-methods] In functional programming, property-based testing has allowed the mathematical specification and testing (if not exhaustive testing) of the expected behaviour of individual functions.
[src:formal-methods/formal-methods] The Object Constraint Language (and specializations such as Java Modeling Language) has allowed object-oriented systems to be formally specified, if not necessarily formally verified.
[src:formal-methods/formal-methods] Another approach to formal methods in software development is to write a specification in some form of logic—usually a variation of first-order logic—and then to directly execute the logic as though it were a program.
[src:formal-methods/formal-methods] The OWL language, based on description logic, is an example.
[src:formal-methods/formal-methods] There is also work on mapping some version of English (or another natural language) automatically to and from logic, as well as executing the logic directly.
[src:formal-methods/formal-methods] Examples are Attempto Controlled English, and Internet Business Logic, which do not seek to control the vocabulary or syntax.
[src:formal-methods/formal-methods] A feature of systems that support bidirectional English–logic mapping and direct execution of the logic is that they can be made to explain their results, in English, at the business or scientific level.
[src:formal-methods/formal-methods] Semi-formal methods are formalisms and languages that are not considered fully "formal".
[src:formal-methods/formal-methods] It defers the task of completing the semantics to a later stage, which is then done either by human interpretation or by interpretation through software like code or test case generators.
[src:formal-methods/formal-methods] Some practitioners believe that the formal methods community has overemphasized full formalization of a specification or design.
[src:formal-methods/formal-methods] They contend that the expressiveness of the languages involved, as well as the complexity of the systems being modelled, make full formalization a difficult and expensive task.
[src:formal-methods/formal-methods] As an alternative, various *lightweight* formal methods, which emphasize partial specification and focused application, have been proposed.
[src:formal-methods/formal-methods] Examples of this lightweight approach to formal methods include the Alloy object modelling notation, Denney's synthesis of some aspects of the Z notation with use case driven development, and the CSK VDM Tools.
[src:formal-methods/formal-methods] There are a variety of formal methods and notations available.
[src:formal-methods/formal-methods] Many problems in formal methods are NP-hard, but can be solved in cases arising in practice.
[src:formal-methods/formal-methods] For example, the Boolean satisfiability problem is NP-complete by the Cook–Levin theorem, but SAT solvers can solve a variety of large instances.
[src:formal-methods/formal-methods] There are "solvers" for a variety of problems that arise in formal methods, and there are many periodic competitions to evaluate the state-of-the-art in solving such problems.
[src:formal-methods/formal-specification] In computer science, **formal specifications** are mathematically based techniques whose purpose is to help with the implementation of systems and software.
[src:formal-methods/formal-specification] They are used to describe a system, to analyze its behavior, and to aid in its design by verifying key properties of interest through rigorous and effective reasoning tools.
[src:formal-methods/formal-specification] These specifications are *formal* in the sense that they have a syntax, their semantics fall within one domain, and they are able to be used to infer useful information.
[src:formal-methods/formal-specification] In each passing decade, computer systems have become increasingly more powerful and, as a result, they have become more impactful to society.
[src:formal-methods/formal-specification] Because of this, better techniques are needed to assist in the design and implementation of reliable software.
[src:formal-methods/formal-specification] Established engineering disciplines use mathematical analysis as the foundation of creating and validating product design.
[src:formal-methods/formal-specification] Formal specifications are one such way to achieve this in software engineering reliability as once predicted.
[src:formal-methods/formal-specification] Other methods such as testing are more commonly used to enhance code quality.
[src:formal-methods/formal-specification] Given such a specification, it is possible to use formal verification techniques to demonstrate that a system design is correct with respect to its specification.
[src:formal-methods/formal-specification] This allows incorrect system designs to be revised before any major investments have been made into an actual implementation.
[src:formal-methods/formal-specification] Another approach is to use provably correct refinement steps to transform a specification into a design, which is ultimately transformed into an implementation that is *correct by construction*.
[src:formal-methods/formal-specification] A formal specification is *not* an implementation, but rather it may be used to develop an implementation.
[src:formal-methods/formal-specification] Formal specifications describe *what* a system should do, not *how* the system should do it.
[src:formal-methods/formal-specification] A good specification must have some of the following attributes: adequate, internally consistent, unambiguous, complete, satisfied, minimal.
[src:formal-methods/formal-specification] One of the main reasons there is interest in formal specifications is that they will provide an ability to perform proofs on software implementations.
[src:formal-methods/formal-specification] These proofs may be used to validate a specification, verify correctness of design, or to prove that a program satisfies a specification.
[src:formal-methods/formal-specification] A design (or implementation) cannot ever be declared “correct” on its own.
[src:formal-methods/formal-specification] It can only ever be “correct with respect to a given specification”.
[src:formal-methods/formal-specification] Whether the formal specification correctly describes the problem to be solved is a separate issue.
[src:formal-methods/formal-specification] It is also a difficult issue to address since it ultimately concerns the problem constructing abstracted formal representations of an informal concrete problem domain, and such an abstraction step is not amenable to formal proof.
[src:formal-methods/formal-specification] However, it is possible to validate a specification by proving “challenge” theorems concerning properties that the specification is expected to exhibit.
[src:formal-methods/formal-specification] If correct, these theorems reinforce the specifier's understanding of the specification and its relationship with the underlying problem domain.
[src:formal-methods/formal-specification] If not, the specification probably needs to be changed to better reflect the domain understanding of those involved with producing (and implementing) the specification.
[src:formal-methods/formal-specification] Formal methods of software development are not widely used in industry.
[src:formal-methods/formal-specification] Most companies do not consider it cost-effective to apply them in their software development processes.
[src:formal-methods/formal-specification] Formal specification techniques have existed in various domains and on various scales for quite some time.
[src:formal-methods/formal-specification] Implementations of formal specifications will differ depending on what kind of system they are attempting to model, how they are applied and at what point in the software life cycle they have been introduced.
[src:formal-methods/formal-specification] In addition to the above paradigms, there are ways to apply certain heuristics to help improve the creation of these specifications.
[src:formal-methods/formal-specification] The paper referenced here best discusses heuristics to use when designing a specification.
[src:formal-methods/formal-specification] They do so by applying a divide-and-conquer approach.
[src:formal-methods/formal-specification] The Z notation is an example of a leading formal specification language.
[src:formal-methods/formal-specification] Others include the Specification Language (VDM-SL) of the Vienna Development Method and the Abstract Machine Notation (AMN) of the B-Method.
[src:formal-methods/formal-specification] In the Web services area, formal specification is often used to describe non-functional properties (Web services quality of service).
[src:formal-methods/formal-verification] In the context of hardware and software systems, **formal verification** is the act of proving or disproving the correctness of a system with respect to a certain formal specification or property, using formal methods of mathematics.
[src:formal-methods/formal-verification] Formal verification is a key incentive for formal specification of systems, and is at the core of formal methods.
[src:formal-methods/formal-verification] It represents an important dimension of analysis and verification in electronic design automation and is one approach to software verification.
[src:formal-methods/formal-verification] The use of formal verification enables the highest Evaluation Assurance Level (EAL7) in the framework of common criteria for computer security certification.
[src:formal-methods/formal-verification] Formal verification can be helpful in proving the correctness of systems such as: cryptographic protocols, combinational circuits, digital circuits with internal memory, and software expressed as source code in a programming language.
[src:formal-methods/formal-verification] Prominent examples of verified software systems include the CompCert verified C compiler and the seL4 high-assurance operating system kernel.
[src:formal-methods/formal-verification] The verification of these systems is done by ensuring the existence of a formal proof of a mathematical model of the system.
[src:formal-methods/formal-verification] Model checking involves a systematic and exhaustive exploration of the mathematical model.
[src:formal-methods/formal-verification] Such exploration is possible for finite models, but also for some infinite models, where infinite sets of states can be effectively represented finitely by using abstraction or taking advantage of symmetry.
[src:formal-methods/formal-verification] Usually, this consists of exploring all states and transitions in the model, by using smart and domain-specific abstraction techniques to consider whole groups of states in a single operation and reduce computing time.
[src:formal-methods/formal-verification] Implementation techniques include state space enumeration, symbolic state space enumeration, abstract interpretation, symbolic simulation, abstraction refinement.
[src:formal-methods/formal-verification] The properties to be verified are often described in temporal logics, such as linear temporal logic (LTL), Property Specification Language (PSL), SystemVerilog Assertions (SVA), or computational tree logic (CTL).
[src:formal-methods/formal-verification] Another approach is deductive verification.
[src:formal-methods/formal-verification] Formal verification of software programs involves proving that a program satisfies a formal specification of its behavior.
[src:formal-methods/formal-verification] Subareas of formal verification include deductive verification (see above), abstract interpretation, automated theorem proving, type systems, and lightweight formal methods.
[src:formal-methods/formal-verification] A promising type-based verification approach is dependently typed programming, in which the types of functions include (at least part of) those functions' specifications, and type-checking the code establishes its correctness against those specifications.
[src:formal-methods/formal-verification] Fully featured dependently typed languages support deductive verification as a special case.
[src:formal-methods/formal-verification] Another complementary approach is program derivation, in which efficient code is produced from functional specifications by a series of correctness-preserving steps.
[src:formal-methods/formal-verification] An example of this approach is the Bird–Meertens formalism, and this approach can be seen as another form of program synthesis.
[src:formal-methods/formal-verification] These techniques can be *sound*, meaning that the verified properties can be logically deduced from the semantics, or *unsound*, meaning that there is no such guarantee.
[src:formal-methods/formal-verification] A sound technique yields a result only once it has covered the entire space of possibilities.
[src:formal-methods/formal-verification] An example of an unsound technique is one that covers only a subset of the possibilities, for instance only integers up to a certain number, and give a "good-enough" result.
[src:formal-methods/formal-verification] Techniques can also be *decidable*, meaning that their algorithmic implementations are guaranteed to terminate with an answer, or undecidable, meaning that they may never terminate.
[src:formal-methods/formal-verification] By bounding the scope of possibilities, unsound techniques that are decidable might be able to be constructed when no decidable sound techniques are available.
[src:formal-methods/formal-verification] Verification is one aspect of testing a product's fitness for purpose.
[src:formal-methods/formal-verification] Often one refers to the overall checking process as V & V.
[src:formal-methods/formal-verification] The verification process consists of static/structural and dynamic/behavioral aspects.
[src:formal-methods/formal-verification] E.g., for a software product one can inspect the source code (static) and run against specific test cases (dynamic).
[src:formal-methods/formal-verification] Validation usually can be done only dynamically, i.e., the product is tested by putting it through typical and atypical usages ("Does it satisfactorily meet all use cases?").
[src:formal-methods/formal-verification] Program repair is performed with respect to an oracle, encompassing the desired functionality of the program which is used for validation of the generated fix.
[src:formal-methods/formal-verification] A simple example is a test-suite—the input/output pairs specify the functionality of the program.
[src:formal-methods/formal-verification] A variety of techniques are employed, most notably using satisfiability modulo theories (SMT) solvers, and genetic programming, using evolutionary computing to generate and evaluate possible candidates for fixes.
[src:formal-methods/formal-verification] The former method is deterministic, while the latter is randomized.
[src:formal-methods/formal-verification] For example, the Nopol tool encodes the repair of buggy conditional statements as an SMT instance to determinstically generate patches for if conditions and missing preconditions.
[src:formal-methods/formal-verification] Program repair combines techniques from formal verification and program synthesis.
[src:formal-methods/formal-verification] Fault-localization techniques in formal verification are used to compute program points which might be possible bug-locations, which can be targeted by the synthesis modules.
[src:formal-methods/formal-verification] Repair systems often focus on a small pre-defined class of bugs in order to reduce the search space.
[src:formal-methods/formal-verification] Industrial use is limited owing to the computational cost of existing techniques.
[src:formal-methods/formal-verification] The growth in complexity of designs increases the importance of formal verification techniques in the hardware industry.
[src:formal-methods/formal-verification] At present, formal verification is used by most or all leading hardware companies, but its use in the software industry is still languishing.
[src:formal-methods/formal-verification] This could be attributed to the greater need in the hardware industry, where errors have greater commercial significance.
[src:formal-methods/formal-verification] Because of the potential subtle interactions between components, it is increasingly difficult to exercise a realistic set of possibilities by simulation.
[src:formal-methods/formal-verification] Important aspects of hardware design are amenable to automated proof methods, making formal verification easier to introduce and more productive.
[src:formal-methods/formal-verification] As of 2011, several operating systems have been formally verified: NICTA's Secure Embedded L4 microkernel, sold commercially as seL4 by OK Labs; OSEK/VDX based real-time operating system ORIENTAIS by East China Normal University; Green Hills Software's Integrity operating system; and SYSGO's PikeOS.
[src:formal-methods/formal-verification] In 2016, a team led by Zhong Shao at Yale developed a formally verified operating system kernel called CertiKOS.
[src:formal-methods/formal-verification] As of 2017, formal verification has been applied to the design of large computer networks through a mathematical model of the network, and as part of a new network technology category, intent-based networking.
[src:formal-methods/formal-verification] Network software vendors that offer formal verification solutions include Cisco Forward Networks and Veriflow Systems.
[src:formal-methods/formal-verification] The SPARK programming language provides a toolset which enables software development with formal verification and is used in several high-integrity systems.
[src:formal-methods/formal-verification] The CompCert C compiler is a formally verified C compiler implementing the majority of ISO C.
[src:formal-methods/hoare-logic] The central feature of **Hoare logic** is the **Hoare triple**.
[src:formal-methods/hoare-logic] A triple describes how the execution of a piece of code changes the state of the computation.
[src:formal-methods/hoare-logic] where P and Q are *assertions* and C is a *command*.
[src:formal-methods/hoare-logic] P is named the *precondition* and Q the *postcondition*: when the precondition is met, executing the command establishes the postcondition.
[src:formal-methods/hoare-logic] Assertions are formulae in predicate logic.
[src:formal-methods/hoare-logic] Hoare logic provides axioms and inference rules for all the constructs of a simple imperative programming language.
[src:formal-methods/hoare-logic] In addition to the rules for the simple language in Hoare's original paper, rules for other language constructs have been developed since then by Hoare and many other researchers.
[src:formal-methods/hoare-logic] There are rules for concurrency, procedures, jumps, and pointers.
[src:formal-methods/hoare-logic] Using standard Hoare logic, only partial correctness can be proven.
[src:formal-methods/hoare-logic] Total correctness additionally requires termination, which can be proven separately or with an extended version of the While rule.
[src:formal-methods/hoare-logic] Thus, the intuitive reading of a Hoare triple is: Whenever P holds of the state before the execution of C , then Q will hold afterwards, or C does not terminate.
[src:formal-methods/hoare-logic] In the latter case, there is no "after", so Q can be any statement at all.
[src:formal-methods/hoare-logic] Indeed, one can choose Q to be false to express that C does not terminate.
[src:formal-methods/hoare-logic] The empty statement rule asserts that the skip statement does not change the state of the program, thus whatever holds true before skip also holds true afterwards.
[src:formal-methods/hoare-logic] The assignment axiom states that, after the assignment, any predicate that was previously true for the right-hand side of the assignment now holds for the variable.
[src:formal-methods/hoare-logic] Formally, let P be an assertion in which the variable x is free.
[src:formal-methods/hoare-logic] where $P[E/x]$ denotes the assertion P in which each free occurrence of x has been replaced by the expression E.
[src:formal-methods/hoare-logic] The assignment axiom scheme means that the truth of $P[E/x]$ is equivalent to the after-assignment truth of P.
[src:formal-methods/hoare-logic] Thus, were $P[E/x]$ true before the assignment, by the assignment axiom, then P would be true afterwards.
[src:formal-methods/hoare-logic] Conversely, were $P[E/x]$ false (i.e. $\neg P[E/x]$ true) prior to the assignment statement, P must then be false afterwards.
[src:formal-methods/hoare-logic] All preconditions that are not modified by the expression can be carried over to the postcondition.
[src:formal-methods/hoare-logic] In the first example, assigning $y:=x+1$ does not change the fact that $x+1=43$ , so both statements may appear in the postcondition.
[src:formal-methods/hoare-logic] Formally, this result is obtained by applying the axiom schema with P being ( $y=43$ and $x+1=43$ ), which yields $P[(x+1)/y]$ being ( $x+1=43$ and $x+1=43$ ), which can in turn be simplified to the given precondition $x+1=43$ .
[src:formal-methods/hoare-logic] The assignment axiom scheme is equivalent to saying that to find the precondition, first take the post-condition and replace all occurrences of the left-hand side of the assignment with the right-hand side of the assignment.
[src:formal-methods/hoare-logic] While a given postcondition P uniquely determines the precondition $P[E/x]$ , the converse is not true.
[src:formal-methods/hoare-logic] are valid instances of the assignment axiom scheme.
[src:formal-methods/hoare-logic] The assignment axiom proposed by Hoare *does not apply* when more than one name may refer to the same stored value.
[src:formal-methods/hoare-logic] is wrong if x and y refer to the same variable (aliasing), although it is a proper instance of the assignment axiom scheme (with both $\{P\}$ and $\{P[2/x]\}$ being $\{y=3\}$ ).
[src:formal-methods/hoare-logic] Another example is shown in the right box.
[src:formal-methods/hoare-logic] The conditional rule states that a postcondition Q common to then and else part is also a postcondition of the whole if...endif statement.
[src:formal-methods/hoare-logic] In the then and the else part, the unnegated and negated condition B can be added to the precondition P, respectively.
[src:formal-methods/hoare-logic] The condition, B, must not have side effects.
[src:formal-methods/hoare-logic] An example is given in the next section.
[src:formal-methods/hoare-logic] This rule was not contained in Hoare's original publication.
[src:formal-methods/hoare-logic] the conditional rule can be derived from the other Hoare rules.
[src:formal-methods/hoare-logic] In a similar way, rules for other derived program constructs, like for loop, do...until loop, switch, break, continue can be reduced by program transformation to the rules from Hoare's original paper.
[src:formal-methods/hoare-logic] This rule permits strengthening the precondition $P_{2}$ and/or to weaken the postcondition $Q_{2}$ .
[src:formal-methods/hoare-logic] It is used, e.g., to achieve literally identical postconditions for the then and the else part.
[src:formal-methods/hoare-logic] The consequence rule is needed to strengthen the precondition $\{-1\leq x<15\}$ obtained from the assignment rule to $\{0\leq x<15\}$ required for the conditional rule.
[src:formal-methods/hoare-logic] hence the consequence rule has to be applied with $P_{1}$ and $P_{2}$ being $\{x=15\}$ and $\{{\texttt {true}}\}$ , respectively, to strengthen again the precondition.
[src:formal-methods/hoare-logic] Informally, the effect of the consequence rule is to "forget" that $\{x=15\}$ is known at the entry of the else part, since the assignment rule used for the else part doesn't need that information.
[src:formal-methods/hoare-logic] Here P is the loop invariant, which is to be preserved by the loop body S.
[src:formal-methods/hoare-logic] After the loop is finished, this invariant P still holds, and moreover $\neg B$ must have caused the loop to end.
[src:formal-methods/hoare-logic] As in the conditional rule, B must not have side effects.
[src:formal-methods/hoare-logic] which is easily obtained by the assignment rule.
[src:formal-methods/hoare-logic] Finally, the postcondition $\{\neg x<10\wedge x\leq 10\}$ can be simplified to $\{x=10\}$ .
[src:formal-methods/hoare-logic] which follows from the skip rule and the consequence rule.
[src:formal-methods/hoare-logic] In fact, the strange program is *partially* correct: if it happened to terminate, it is certain that x must have contained (by chance) the value of a's square root.
[src:formal-methods/hoare-logic] In all other cases, it will not terminate; therefore, it is not *totally* correct.
[src:formal-methods/hoare-logic] If the above ordinary while rule is replaced by the following one, the Hoare calculus can also be used to prove total correctness, i.e., termination as well as partial correctness.
[src:formal-methods/hoare-logic] Commonly, square brackets are used here instead of curly braces to indicate the different notion of program correctness.
[src:formal-methods/hoare-logic] In this rule, in addition to maintaining the loop invariant, one also proves termination by way of an expression t, called the loop variant, whose value strictly decreases with respect to a well-founded relation < on some domain set D during each iteration.
[src:formal-methods/hoare-logic] Since < is well-founded, a strictly decreasing chain of members of D can have only finite length, so t cannot keep decreasing forever.
[src:formal-methods/hoare-logic] Given the loop invariant P, the condition B must imply that t is not a minimal element of D, for otherwise the body S could not decrease t any further, i.e. the premise of the rule would be false.
[src:formal-methods/hoare-logic] the while rule for total correctness can be applied with e.g.
[src:formal-methods/hoare-logic] Informally speaking, we have to prove that the distance $10-x$ decreases in every loop cycle, while it always remains non-negative; this process can go on only for a finite number of cycles.
[src:formal-methods/hoare-logic] For the second example of the previous section, of course, no expression t can be found that is decreased by the empty loop body, hence termination cannot be proved.
[src:formal-methods/invariant-mathematics] In mathematics, an **invariant** is a property of a mathematical object (or a class of mathematical objects) which remains unchanged after operations or transformations of a certain type are applied to the objects.
[src:formal-methods/invariant-mathematics] The particular class of objects and type of transformations are usually indicated by the context in which the term is used.
[src:formal-methods/invariant-mathematics] For example, the area of a triangle is an invariant with respect to isometries of the Euclidean plane.
[src:formal-methods/invariant-mathematics] The phrases "invariant under" and "invariant to" a transformation are both used.
[src:formal-methods/invariant-mathematics] More generally, an invariant with respect to an equivalence relation is a property that is constant on each equivalence class.
[src:formal-methods/invariant-mathematics] Invariants are used in diverse areas of mathematics such as geometry, topology, algebra and discrete mathematics.
[src:formal-methods/invariant-mathematics] Some important classes of transformations are defined by an invariant they leave unchanged.
[src:formal-methods/invariant-mathematics] For example, conformal maps are defined as transformations of the plane that preserve angles.
[src:formal-methods/invariant-mathematics] The discovery of invariants is an important step in the process of classifying mathematical objects.
[src:formal-methods/invariant-mathematics] A simple example of invariance is expressed in our ability to count.
[src:formal-methods/invariant-mathematics] For a finite set of objects of any kind, there is a number to which we always arrive, regardless of the order in which we count the objects in the set.
[src:formal-methods/invariant-mathematics] The quantity—a cardinal number—is associated with the set, and is invariant under the process of counting.
[src:formal-methods/invariant-mathematics] An identity is an equation that remains true for all values of its variables.
[src:formal-methods/invariant-mathematics] There are also inequalities that remain true when the values of their variables change.
[src:formal-methods/invariant-mathematics] The distance between two points on a number line is not changed by adding the same quantity to both numbers.
[src:formal-methods/invariant-mathematics] On the other hand, multiplication does not have this same property, as distance is not invariant under multiplication.
[src:formal-methods/invariant-mathematics] Angles and ratios of distances are invariant under scalings, rotations, translations and reflections.
[src:formal-methods/invariant-mathematics] These transformations produce similar shapes, which are the basis of trigonometry.
[src:formal-methods/invariant-mathematics] In contrast, angles and ratios are not invariant under non-uniform scaling (such as stretching).
[src:formal-methods/invariant-mathematics] The sum of a triangle's interior angles (180°) is invariant under all the above operations.
[src:formal-methods/invariant-mathematics] As another example, all circles are similar: they can be transformed into each other, and the ratio of the circumference to the diameter is invariant (denoted by the Greek letter π (pi)).
[src:formal-methods/invariant-mathematics] The MU puzzle is a good example of a logical problem where determining an invariant is of use for an impossibility proof.
[src:formal-methods/invariant-mathematics] In light of this, one might wonder whether it is possible to convert MI into MU, using only these four transformation rules.
[src:formal-methods/invariant-mathematics] One could spend many hours applying these transformation rules to strings.
[src:formal-methods/invariant-mathematics] However, it might be quicker to find a property that is invariant to all rules (that is, not changed by any of them), and that demonstrates that getting to MU is impossible.
[src:formal-methods/invariant-mathematics] By looking at the puzzle from a logical standpoint, one might realize that the only way to get rid of any I's is to have three consecutive I's in the string.
[src:formal-methods/invariant-mathematics] This is an invariant to the problem, if for each of the transformation rules the following holds: if the invariant held before applying the rule, it will also hold after applying it.
[src:formal-methods/invariant-mathematics] The table above shows clearly that the invariant holds for each of the possible transformation rules, which means that whichever rule one picks, at whatever state, if the number of I's was not a multiple of three before applying the rule, then it will not be afterwards either.
[src:formal-methods/invariant-mathematics] Given that there is a single I in the starting string MI, and one is not a multiple of three, one can then conclude that it is impossible to go from MI to MU (as the number of I's will never be a multiple of three).
[src:formal-methods/invariant-mathematics] A subset *S* of the domain *U* of a mapping *T*: *U* → *U* is an **invariant set** under the mapping when $x\in S\iff T(x)\in S.$ The elements of *S* are not necessarily fixed, even though the set *S* is fixed in the power set of *U*.
[src:formal-methods/invariant-mathematics] (Some authors use the terminology *setwise invariant,* vs.
[src:formal-methods/invariant-mathematics] *pointwise invariant,* to distinguish between these cases.) For example, a circle is an invariant subset of the plane under a rotation about the circle's center.
[src:formal-methods/invariant-mathematics] Further, a conical surface is invariant as a set under a homothety of space.
[src:formal-methods/invariant-mathematics] An invariant set of an operation *T* is also said to be **stable under** *T*.
[src:formal-methods/invariant-mathematics] For example, the normal subgroups that are so important in group theory are those subgroups that are stable under the inner automorphisms of the ambient group.
[src:formal-methods/invariant-mathematics] In linear algebra, if a linear transformation *T* has an eigenvector **v**, then the line through **0** and **v** is an invariant set under *T*, in which case the eigenvectors span an invariant subspace which is stable under *T*.
[src:formal-methods/invariant-mathematics] When *T* is a screw displacement, the screw axis is an invariant line, though if the pitch is non-zero, *T* has no fixed points.
[src:formal-methods/invariant-mathematics] In probability theory and ergodic theory, invariant sets are usually defined via the stronger property $x\in S\Leftrightarrow T(x)\in S.$ When the map T is measurable, invariant sets form a sigma-algebra, the invariant sigma-algebra.
[src:formal-methods/invariant-mathematics] The notion of invariance is formalized in three different ways in mathematics: via group actions, presentations, and deformation.
[src:formal-methods/invariant-mathematics] Firstly, if one has a group *G* acting on a mathematical object (or set of objects) *X,* then one may ask which points *x* are unchanged, "invariant" under the group action, or under an element *g* of the group.
[src:formal-methods/invariant-mathematics] Frequently, one will have a group acting on a set *X*, which leaves one to determine which objects in an *associated* set *F*(*X*) are invariant.
[src:formal-methods/invariant-mathematics] For example, rotation in the plane about a point leaves the point about which it rotates invariant, while translation in the plane does not leave any points invariant, but does leave all lines parallel to the direction of translation invariant as lines.
[src:formal-methods/invariant-mathematics] Formally, define the set of lines in the plane *P* as *L*(*P*); then a rigid motion of the plane takes lines to lines – the group of rigid motions acts on the set of lines – and one may ask which lines are unchanged by an action.
[src:formal-methods/invariant-mathematics] More importantly, one may define a *function* on a set, such as "radius of a circle in the plane", and then ask if this function is invariant under a group action, such as rigid motions.
[src:formal-methods/invariant-mathematics] Dual to the notion of invariants are *coinvariants,* also known as *orbits,* which formalizes the notion of congruence: objects that can be taken to each other by a group action.
[src:formal-methods/invariant-mathematics] For example, under the group of rigid motions of the plane, the perimeter of a triangle is an invariant, while the set of triangles congruent to a given triangle is a coinvariant.
[src:formal-methods/invariant-mathematics] These are connected as follows: invariants are constant on coinvariants (for example, congruent triangles have the same perimeter), while two objects that agree in the value of one invariant may or may not be congruent (for example, two triangles with the same perimeter need not be congruent).
[src:formal-methods/invariant-mathematics] In classification problems, one might seek to find a complete set of invariants, such that if two objects have the same values for this set of invariants, then they are congruent.
[src:formal-methods/invariant-mathematics] For example, triangles such that all three sides are equal are congruent under rigid motions, via SSS congruence, and thus the lengths of all three sides form a complete set of invariants for triangles.
[src:formal-methods/invariant-mathematics] The three angle measures of a triangle are also invariant under rigid motions, but do not form a complete set as incongruent triangles can share the same angle measures.
[src:formal-methods/invariant-mathematics] However, if one allows scaling in addition to rigid motions, then the AAA similarity criterion shows that this is a complete set of invariants.
[src:formal-methods/invariant-mathematics] Secondly, a function may be defined in terms of some presentation or decomposition of a mathematical object; for instance, the Euler characteristic of a cell complex is defined as the alternating sum of the number of cells in each dimension.
[src:formal-methods/invariant-mathematics] This is the case for the Euler characteristic, and a general method for defining and computing invariants is to define them for a given presentation, and then show that they are independent of the choice of presentation.
[src:formal-methods/invariant-mathematics] Note that there is no notion of a group action in this sense.
[src:formal-methods/invariant-mathematics] Thirdly, if one is studying an object that varies in a family, as is common in algebraic geometry and differential geometry, one may ask if the property is unchanged under perturbation (for example, if an object is constant on families or invariant under change of metric).
[src:formal-methods/invariant-mathematics] In computer science, an invariant is a logical assertion that is always held to be true during a certain phase of execution of a computer program.
[src:formal-methods/invariant-mathematics] For example, a loop invariant is a condition that is true at the beginning and the end of every iteration of a loop.
[src:formal-methods/invariant-mathematics] Invariants are especially useful when reasoning about the correctness of a computer program.
[src:formal-methods/invariant-mathematics] The theory of optimizing compilers, the methodology of design by contract, and formal methods for determining program correctness, all rely heavily on invariants.
[src:formal-methods/invariant-mathematics] Programmers often use assertions in their code to make invariants explicit.
[src:formal-methods/invariant-mathematics] Some object oriented programming languages have a special syntax for specifying class invariants.
[src:formal-methods/invariant-mathematics] Abstract interpretation tools can compute simple invariants of given imperative computer programs.
[src:formal-methods/invariant-mathematics] The kinds of properties that can be found depend on the abstract domains used.
[src:formal-methods/invariant-mathematics] Typical example properties are single integer variable ranges like `0<=x<1024`, relations between several variables like `0<=i-j<2*n-1`, and modulus information like `y%4==0`.
[src:formal-methods/invariant-mathematics] Academic research prototypes also consider simple properties of pointer structures.
[src:formal-methods/invariant-mathematics] More sophisticated invariants generally have to be provided manually.
[src:formal-methods/invariant-mathematics] In particular, when verifying an imperative program using Hoare logic, a loop invariant has to be provided manually for each loop in the program, which is one of the reasons that this approach is generally impractical for most programs.
[src:formal-methods/invariant-mathematics] In the context of the above MU puzzle example, there is currently no general automated tool that can detect that a derivation from MI to MU is impossible using only the rules 1–4.
[src:formal-methods/invariant-mathematics] However, once the abstraction from the string to the number of its "I"s has been made by hand, leading, for example, to the following C program, an abstract interpretation tool will be able to detect that `ICount%3` cannot be 0, and hence the "while"-loop will never terminate.
[src:formal-methods/model-checking] In computer science, **model checking** or **property checking** is a method for checking whether a finite-state model of a system meets a given specification (also known as correctness).
[src:formal-methods/model-checking] This is typically associated with hardware or software systems, where the specification contains liveness requirements (such as avoidance of livelock) as well as safety requirements (such as avoidance of states representing a system crash).
[src:formal-methods/model-checking] In order to solve such a problem algorithmically, both the model of the system and its specification are formulated in some precise mathematical language.
[src:formal-methods/model-checking] To this end, the problem is formulated as a task in logic, namely to check whether a structure satisfies a given logical formula.
[src:formal-methods/model-checking] This general concept applies to many kinds of logic and many kinds of structures.
[src:formal-methods/model-checking] A simple model-checking problem consists of verifying whether a formula in the propositional logic is satisfied by a given structure.
[src:formal-methods/model-checking] Property checking is used for verification when two descriptions are not equivalent.
[src:formal-methods/model-checking] During refinement, the specification is complemented with details that are unnecessary in the higher-level specification.
[src:formal-methods/model-checking] There is no need to verify the newly introduced properties against the original specification since this is not possible.
[src:formal-methods/model-checking] Therefore, the strict bi-directional equivalence check is relaxed to a one-way property check.
[src:formal-methods/model-checking] The implementation or design is regarded as a model of the system, whereas the specifications are properties that the model must satisfy.
[src:formal-methods/model-checking] An important class of model-checking methods has been developed for checking models of hardware and software designs where the specification is given by a temporal logic formula.
[src:formal-methods/model-checking] Pioneering work in temporal logic specification was done by Amir Pnueli, who received the 1996 Turing award for "seminal work introducing temporal logic into computing science".
[src:formal-methods/model-checking] Model checking began with the pioneering work of E.
[src:formal-methods/model-checking] Clarke, Emerson, and Sifakis shared the 2007 Turing Award for their seminal work founding and developing the field of model checking.
[src:formal-methods/model-checking] Model checking is most often applied to hardware designs.
[src:formal-methods/model-checking] For software, because of undecidability (see computability theory) the approach cannot be fully algorithmic, apply to all systems, and always give an answer; in the general case, it may fail to prove or disprove a given property.
[src:formal-methods/model-checking] In embedded-systems hardware, it is possible to validate a specification delivered, e.g., by means of UML activity diagrams or control-interpreted Petri nets.
[src:formal-methods/model-checking] The structure is usually given as a source code description in an industrial hardware description language or a special-purpose language.
[src:formal-methods/model-checking] Such a program corresponds to a finite-state machine (FSM), i.e., a directed graph consisting of nodes (or vertices) and edges.
[src:formal-methods/model-checking] A set of atomic propositions is associated with each node, typically stating which memory elements are one.
[src:formal-methods/model-checking] The nodes represent states of a system, the edges represent possible transitions that may alter the state, while the atomic propositions represent the basic properties that hold at a point of execution.
[src:formal-methods/model-checking] Formally, the problem can be stated as follows: given a desired property, expressed as a temporal logic formula p , and a structure M with initial state s , decide if $M,s\models p$ .
[src:formal-methods/model-checking] If M is finite, as it is in hardware, model checking reduces to a graph search.
[src:formal-methods/model-checking] Instead of enumerating reachable states one at a time, the state space can sometimes be traversed more efficiently by considering large numbers of states at a single step.
[src:formal-methods/model-checking] When such state-space traversal is based on representations of a set of states and transition relations as logical formulas, binary decision diagrams (BDD) or other related data structures, the model-checking method is *symbolic*.
[src:formal-methods/model-checking] Historically, the first symbolic methods used BDDs.
[src:formal-methods/model-checking] After the success of propositional satisfiability in solving the planning problem in artificial intelligence (see satplan) in 1996, the same approach was generalized to model checking for linear temporal logic (LTL): the planning problem corresponds to model checking for safety properties.
[src:formal-methods/model-checking] This method is known as bounded model checking.
[src:formal-methods/model-checking] The success of Boolean satisfiability solvers in bounded model checking led to the widespread use of satisfiability solvers in symbolic model checking.
[src:formal-methods/model-checking] One example of such a system requirement: *Between the time an elevator is called at a floor and the time it opens its doors at that floor, the elevator can arrive at that floor at most twice*.
[src:formal-methods/model-checking] Here, $\Box$ should be read as "always", $\Diamond$ as "eventually", ${\mathcal {U}}$ as "until" and the other symbols are standard logical symbols, $\lor$ for "or", $\land$ for "and" and $\lnot$ for "not".
[src:formal-methods/model-checking] Model-checking tools face a combinatorial blow up of the state-space, commonly known as the state explosion problem, that must be addressed to solve most real-world problems.
[src:formal-methods/model-checking] There are several approaches to combat this problem.
[src:formal-methods/model-checking] Bounded model-checking algorithms unroll the FSM for a fixed number of steps, k , and check whether a property violation can occur in k or fewer steps.
[src:formal-methods/model-checking] This typically involves encoding the restricted model as an instance of SAT.
[src:formal-methods/model-checking] The process can be repeated with larger and larger values of k until all possible violations have been ruled out (cf.
[src:formal-methods/model-checking] Iterative deepening depth-first search).
[src:formal-methods/model-checking] Abstraction attempts to prove properties of a system by first simplifying it.
[src:formal-methods/model-checking] The simplified system usually does not satisfy exactly the same properties as the original one so that a process of refinement may be necessary.
[src:formal-methods/model-checking] Generally, one requires the abstraction to be *sound* (the properties proved on the abstraction are true of the original system); however, sometimes the abstraction is not *complete* (not all true properties of the original system are true of the abstraction).
[src:formal-methods/model-checking] An example of abstraction is to ignore the values of non-Boolean variables and to only consider Boolean variables and the control flow of the program; such an abstraction, though it may appear coarse, may, in fact, be sufficient to prove e.g. properties of mutual exclusion.
[src:formal-methods/model-checking] Counterexample-guided abstraction refinement (CEGAR) begins checking with a coarse (i.e. imprecise) abstraction and iteratively refines it.
[src:formal-methods/model-checking] When a violation (i.e. counterexample) is found, the tool analyzes it for feasibility (i.e., is the violation genuine or the result of an incomplete abstraction?).
[src:formal-methods/model-checking] If the violation is feasible, it is reported to the user.
[src:formal-methods/model-checking] If it is not, the proof of infeasibility is used to refine the abstraction and checking begins again.
[src:formal-methods/model-checking] Model-checking tools were initially developed to reason about the logical correctness of discrete state systems, but have since been extended to deal with real-time and limited forms of hybrid systems.
[src:formal-methods/model-checking] Model checking is also studied in the field of computational complexity theory.
[src:formal-methods/model-checking] This problem is in the circuit class **AC0**.
[src:formal-methods/model-checking] These results have been extended to the task of enumerating all solutions to a first-order formula with free variables.
[src:formal-methods/satisfiability-modulo-theories] In computer science and mathematical logic, **satisfiability modulo theories** (**SMT**) is the problem of determining whether a mathematical formula is satisfiable.
[src:formal-methods/satisfiability-modulo-theories] It generalizes the Boolean satisfiability problem (SAT) to more complex formulas involving real numbers, integers, and/or various data structures such as lists, arrays, bit vectors, and strings.
[src:formal-methods/satisfiability-modulo-theories] The name is derived from the fact that these expressions are interpreted within ("modulo") a certain formal theory in first-order logic with equality (often disallowing quantifiers).
[src:formal-methods/satisfiability-modulo-theories] **SMT solvers** are tools that aim to solve the SMT problem for a practical subset of inputs.
[src:formal-methods/satisfiability-modulo-theories] SMT solvers such as Z3 and cvc5 have been used as a building block for a wide range of applications across computer science, including in automated theorem proving, program analysis, program verification, and software testing.
[src:formal-methods/satisfiability-modulo-theories] Since Boolean satisfiability is already NP-complete, the SMT problem is typically NP-hard, and for many theories it is undecidable.
[src:formal-methods/satisfiability-modulo-theories] Researchers study which theories or subsets of theories lead to a decidable SMT problem and the computational complexity of decidable cases.
[src:formal-methods/satisfiability-modulo-theories] The resulting decision procedures are often implemented directly in SMT solvers; see, for instance, the decidability of Presburger arithmetic.
[src:formal-methods/satisfiability-modulo-theories] SMT can be thought of as a constraint satisfaction problem and thus a certain formalized approach to constraint programming.
[src:formal-methods/satisfiability-modulo-theories] Formally speaking, an SMT instance is a formula in first-order logic, where some function and predicate symbols have additional interpretations, and SMT is the problem of determining whether such a formula is satisfiable.
[src:formal-methods/satisfiability-modulo-theories] In other words, imagine an instance of the Boolean satisfiability problem (SAT) in which some of the binary variables are replaced by predicates over a suitable set of non-binary variables.
[src:formal-methods/satisfiability-modulo-theories] A predicate is a binary-valued function of non-binary variables.
[src:formal-methods/satisfiability-modulo-theories] Example predicates include linear inequalities (e.g., $3x+2y-z\geq 4$ ) or equalities involving uninterpreted terms and function symbols (e.g., $f(f(u,v),v)=f(u,v)$ where f is some unspecified function of two arguments).
[src:formal-methods/satisfiability-modulo-theories] These predicates are classified according to each respective theory assigned.
[src:formal-methods/satisfiability-modulo-theories] Other theories include the theories of arrays and list structures (useful for modeling and verifying computer programs), and the theory of bit vectors (useful in modeling and verifying hardware designs).
[src:formal-methods/satisfiability-modulo-theories] Subtheories are also possible: for example, difference logic is a sub-theory of linear arithmetic in which each inequality is restricted to have the form $x-y>c$ for variables x and y and constant c .
[src:formal-methods/satisfiability-modulo-theories] The examples above show the use of linear integer arithmetic over inequalities.
[src:formal-methods/satisfiability-modulo-theories] Most SMT solvers support only quantifier-free fragments of their logics.
[src:formal-methods/satisfiability-modulo-theories] There is substantial overlap between SMT solving and automated theorem proving (ATP).
[src:formal-methods/satisfiability-modulo-theories] Generally, automated theorem provers focus on supporting full first-order logic with quantifiers, whereas SMT solvers focus more on supporting various theories (interpreted predicate symbols).
[src:formal-methods/satisfiability-modulo-theories] ATPs excel at problems with lots of quantifiers, whereas SMT solvers do well on large problems without quantifiers.
[src:formal-methods/satisfiability-modulo-theories] The line is blurry enough that some ATPs participate in SMT-COMP, while some SMT solvers participate in CASC.
[src:formal-methods/satisfiability-modulo-theories] An SMT instance is a generalization of a Boolean SAT instance in which various sets of variables are replaced by predicates from a variety of underlying theories.
[src:formal-methods/satisfiability-modulo-theories] SMT formulas provide a much richer modeling language than is possible with Boolean SAT formulas.
[src:formal-methods/satisfiability-modulo-theories] For example, an SMT formula allows one to model the datapath operations of a microprocessor at the word rather than the bit level.
[src:formal-methods/satisfiability-modulo-theories] By comparison, answer set programming is also based on predicates (more precisely, on atomic sentences created from atomic formulas).
[src:formal-methods/satisfiability-modulo-theories] Unlike SMT, answer-set programs do not have quantifiers, and cannot easily express constraints such as linear arithmetic or difference logic—answer set programming is best suited to Boolean problems that reduce to the free theory of uninterpreted functions.
[src:formal-methods/satisfiability-modulo-theories] Implementing 32-bit integers as bitvectors in answer set programming suffers from most of the same problems that early SMT solvers faced: "obvious" identities such as *x* + *y* = *y* + *x* are difficult to deduce.
[src:formal-methods/satisfiability-modulo-theories] Constraint logic programming does provide support for linear arithmetic constraints, but within a completely different theoretical framework.
[src:formal-methods/satisfiability-modulo-theories] SMT solvers have also been extended to solve formulas in higher-order logic.
[src:formal-methods/satisfiability-modulo-theories] This approach, which is referred to as *the eager approach* (or *bitblasting*), has its merits: by pre-processing the SMT formula into an equivalent Boolean SAT formula existing Boolean SAT solvers can be used "as-is" and their performance and capacity improvements leveraged over time.
[src:formal-methods/satisfiability-modulo-theories] This approach is referred to as *the lazy approach*.
[src:formal-methods/satisfiability-modulo-theories] Dubbed DPLL(T), this architecture gives the responsibility of Boolean reasoning to the DPLL-based SAT solver which, in turn, interacts with a solver for theory T through a well-defined interface.
[src:formal-methods/satisfiability-modulo-theories] The theory solver only needs to worry about checking the feasibility of conjunctions of theory predicates passed on to it from the SAT solver as it explores the Boolean search space of the formula.
[src:formal-methods/satisfiability-modulo-theories] For this integration to work well, however, the theory solver must be able to participate in propagation and conflict analysis, i.e., it must be able to infer new facts from already established facts, as well as to supply succinct explanations of infeasibility when theory conflicts arise.
[src:formal-methods/satisfiability-modulo-theories] In other words, the theory solver must be incremental and backtrackable.
[src:formal-methods/satisfiability-modulo-theories] Since full first-order logic is only semidecidable, one line of research attempts to find efficient decision procedures for fragments of first-order logic such as effectively propositional logic.
[src:formal-methods/satisfiability-modulo-theories] Examples of monotonic theories include graph reachability, collision detection for convex hulls, minimum cuts, and computation tree logic.
[src:formal-methods/satisfiability-modulo-theories] Every Datalog program can be interpreted as a monotonic theory.
[src:formal-methods/satisfiability-modulo-theories] Most of the common SMT approaches support decidable theories.
[src:formal-methods/satisfiability-modulo-theories] However, many real-world systems, such as an aircraft and its behavior, can only be modelled by means of non-linear arithmetic over the real numbers involving transcendental functions.
[src:formal-methods/satisfiability-modulo-theories] Such problems are, however, undecidable in general.
[src:formal-methods/satisfiability-modulo-theories] (On the other hand, the theory of real closed fields, and thus the full first order theory of the real numbers, are decidable using quantifier elimination.
[src:formal-methods/satisfiability-modulo-theories] This is due to Alfred Tarski.) The first order theory of the natural numbers with addition (but not multiplication), called Presburger arithmetic, is also decidable.
[src:formal-methods/satisfiability-modulo-theories] Since multiplication by constants can be implemented as nested additions, the arithmetic in many computer programs can be expressed using Presburger arithmetic, resulting in decidable formulas.
[src:formal-methods/satisfiability-modulo-theories] The table below summarizes some of the features of the many available SMT solvers.
[src:formal-methods/satisfiability-modulo-theories] The column "SMT-LIB" indicates compatibility with the SMT-LIB language; many systems marked 'yes' may support only older versions of SMT-LIB, or offer only partial support for the language.
[src:formal-methods/satisfiability-modulo-theories] The column "CVC" indicates support for the CVC language.
[src:formal-methods/satisfiability-modulo-theories] The column "DIMACS" indicates support for the DIMACS format.
[src:formal-methods/satisfiability-modulo-theories] Projects differ not only in features and performance, but also in the viability of the surrounding community, its ongoing interest in a project, and its ability to contribute documentation, fixes, tests and enhancements.
[src:formal-methods/satisfiability-modulo-theories] Focuses on generating high quality, compact interpolants.
[src:formal-methods/satisfiability-modulo-theories] Toolbox for strategic and parallel SMT solving consisting of a collection of SMT compliant implementations.
[src:formal-methods/satisfiability-modulo-theories] There are multiple attempts to describe a standardized interface to SMT solvers (and automated theorem provers, a term often used synonymously).
[src:formal-methods/satisfiability-modulo-theories] The most prominent is the SMT-LIB standard, which provides a language based on S-expressions.
[src:formal-methods/satisfiability-modulo-theories] Other standardized formats commonly supported are the DIMACS format supported by many Boolean SAT solvers, and the CVC format used by the CVC automated theorem prover.
[src:formal-methods/satisfiability-modulo-theories] The SMT-LIB format also comes with a number of standardized benchmarks and has enabled a yearly competition between SMT solvers called SMT-COMP.
[src:formal-methods/satisfiability-modulo-theories] Initially, the competition took place during the Computer Aided Verification conference (CAV), but as of 2020 the competition is hosted as part of the SMT Workshop, which is affiliated with the International Joint Conference on Automated Reasoning (IJCAR).
[src:formal-methods/satisfiability-modulo-theories] SMT solvers are useful both for verification, proving the correctness of programs, software testing based on symbolic execution, and for synthesis, generating program fragments by searching over the space of possible programs.
[src:formal-methods/satisfiability-modulo-theories] Outside of software verification, SMT solvers have also been used for type inference and for modelling theoretic scenarios, including modelling actor beliefs in nuclear arms control.
[src:formal-methods/satisfiability-modulo-theories] Computer-aided verification of computer programs often uses SMT solvers.
[src:formal-methods/satisfiability-modulo-theories] A common technique is to translate preconditions, postconditions, loop conditions, and assertions into SMT formulas in order to determine if all properties can hold.
[src:formal-methods/satisfiability-modulo-theories] There are many verifiers built on top of the Z3 SMT solver.
[src:formal-methods/satisfiability-modulo-theories] Boogie is an intermediate verification language that uses Z3 to automatically check simple imperative programs.
[src:formal-methods/satisfiability-modulo-theories] The VCC verifier for concurrent C uses Boogie, as well as Dafny for imperative object-based programs, Chalice for concurrent programs, and Spec# for C#.
[src:formal-methods/satisfiability-modulo-theories] F* is a dependently typed language that uses Z3 to find proofs; the compiler carries these proofs through to produce proof-carrying bytecode.
[src:formal-methods/satisfiability-modulo-theories] The Viper verification infrastructure encodes verification conditions to Z3.
[src:formal-methods/satisfiability-modulo-theories] The sbv library provides SMT-based verification of Haskell programs, and lets the user choose among a number of solvers such as Z3, ABC, Boolector, cvc5, MathSAT and Yices.
[src:formal-methods/satisfiability-modulo-theories] There are also many verifiers built on top of the Alt-Ergo SMT solver.
[src:formal-methods/satisfiability-modulo-theories] Many SMT solvers implement a common interface format called SMTLIB2 (such files usually have the extension "`.smt2`").
[src:formal-methods/satisfiability-modulo-theories] The LiquidHaskell tool implements a refinement type based verifier for Haskell that can use any SMTLIB2 compliant solver, e.g. cvc5, MathSat, or Z3.
[src:formal-methods/satisfiability-modulo-theories] An important application of SMT solvers is symbolic execution for analysis and testing of programs (e.g., concolic testing), aimed particularly at finding security vulnerabilities.
[src:formal-methods/satisfiability-modulo-theories] Example tools in this category include SAGE from Microsoft Research, KLEE, S2E, and Triton.
[src:formal-methods/satisfiability-modulo-theories] SMT solvers that have been used for symbolic-execution applications include Z3, STP Archived 2015-04-06 at the Wayback Machine, the Z3str family of solvers, and Boolector.
[src:formal-methods/satisfiability-modulo-theories] SMT solvers have been integrated with proof assistants, including Rocq and Isabelle/HOL.
[src:formal-methods/satisfiability-modulo-theories] SMT solvers are a core building block in program synthesis, the automated generation of programs from specifications.
[src:formal-methods/satisfiability-modulo-theories] A prominent approach is counterexample-guided inductive synthesis (CEGIS), in which a synthesiser proposes a candidate program that is verified by an SMT solver; counterexamples from failed checks guide the synthesiser until a correct solution is found.
[src:formal-methods/satisfiability-modulo-theories] A related application is automatic program repair: given a buggy program and a test suite, an SMT formula is constructed whose solution yields a patch.
[src:formal-methods/satisfiability-modulo-theories] For example, Nopol encodes the problem of finding a repaired conditional expression as an SMT instance, translating the solution back into a source-code patch for Java programs.
[src:formal-methods/static-program-analysis] The term is usually applied to analysis performed by an automated tool, with human analysis typically being called "program understanding", program comprehension, or code review.
[src:formal-methods/static-program-analysis] In the last of these, software inspection and software walkthroughs are also used.
[src:formal-methods/static-program-analysis] In most cases the analysis is performed on some version of a program's source code, and, in other cases, on some form of its object code.
[src:formal-methods/static-program-analysis] The discipline of static analysis should not be confused with linting, which is the process of checking for coding style mistakes.
[src:formal-methods/static-program-analysis] The sophistication of the analysis performed by tools varies from those that only consider the behaviour of individual statements and declarations, to those that include the complete source code of a program in their analysis.
[src:formal-methods/static-program-analysis] The uses of the information obtained from the analysis vary from highlighting possible coding errors (e.g., the lint tool) to formal methods that mathematically prove properties about a given program (e.g., its behaviour matches that of its specification).
[src:formal-methods/static-program-analysis] Software metrics and reverse engineering can be described as forms of static analysis.
[src:formal-methods/static-program-analysis] Deriving software metrics and static analysis are increasingly deployed together, especially in creation of embedded systems, by defining so-called *software quality objectives*.
[src:formal-methods/static-program-analysis] A growing commercial use of static analysis is in the verification of properties of software used in safety-critical computer systems and locating potentially vulnerable code.
[src:formal-methods/static-program-analysis] Nuclear software: In the UK the Office for Nuclear Regulation (ONR) recommends the use of static analysis on reactor protection systems.
[src:formal-methods/static-program-analysis] Aviation software (in combination with dynamic analysis).
[src:formal-methods/static-program-analysis] Automotive & Machines (functional safety features form an integral part of each automotive product development phase, ISO 26262, section 8).
[src:formal-methods/static-program-analysis] A study in 2012 by VDC Research reported that 28.7% of the embedded software engineers surveyed use static analysis tools and 39.7% expect to use them within 2 years.
[src:formal-methods/static-program-analysis] A study from 2010 found that 60% of the interviewed developers in European research projects made at least use of their basic IDE built-in static analyzers.
[src:formal-methods/static-program-analysis] However, only about 10% employed an additional other (and perhaps more advanced) analysis tool.
[src:formal-methods/static-program-analysis] In the application security industry the name static application security testing (SAST) is also used.
[src:formal-methods/static-program-analysis] SAST is an important part of Security Development Lifecycles (SDLs) such as the SDL defined by Microsoft and a common practice in software companies.
[src:formal-methods/static-program-analysis] The OMG (Object Management Group) published a study regarding the types of software analysis required for software quality measurement and assessment.
[src:formal-methods/static-program-analysis] This document on "How to Deliver Resilient, Secure, Efficient, and Easily Changed IT Systems in Line with CISQ Recommendations" describes three levels of software analysis.
[src:formal-methods/static-program-analysis] Analysis that takes place within a specific program or subroutine, without connecting to the context of that program.
[src:formal-methods/static-program-analysis] Analysis that takes into account the interactions between unit programs, but without being limited to one specific technology or programming language.
[src:formal-methods/static-program-analysis] A further level of software analysis can be defined.
[src:formal-methods/static-program-analysis] Analysis that takes into account the business/mission layer terms, rules and processes that are implemented within the software system for its operation as part of enterprise or program/mission layer activities.
[src:formal-methods/static-program-analysis] These elements are implemented without being limited to one specific technology or programming language and in many cases are distributed across multiple languages, but are statically extracted and analyzed for system understanding for mission assurance.
[src:formal-methods/static-program-analysis] Many static analysis tools use intermediate representations of programs to examine the structure of source code without executing the program.
[src:formal-methods/static-program-analysis] For this purpose, abstract syntax trees (ASTs) are commonly used, since they provide a structured representation of a program's syntactic elements.
[src:formal-methods/static-program-analysis] Formal methods is the term applied to the analysis of software (and computer hardware) whose results are obtained purely through the use of rigorous mathematical methods.
[src:formal-methods/static-program-analysis] The mathematical techniques used include denotational semantics, axiomatic semantics, operational semantics, and abstract interpretation.
[src:formal-methods/static-program-analysis] This result dates from the works of Church, Gödel and Turing in the 1930s (see: Halting problem and Rice's theorem).
[src:formal-methods/static-program-analysis] As with many undecidable questions, one can still attempt to give useful approximate solutions.
[src:formal-methods/static-program-analysis] Data-driven static analysis leverages extensive codebases to infer coding rules and improve the accuracy of the analysis.
[src:formal-methods/static-program-analysis] For instance, one can use all Java open-source packages available on GitHub to learn good analysis strategies.
[src:formal-methods/static-program-analysis] The rule inference can use machine learning techniques.
[src:formal-methods/static-program-analysis] It is also possible to learn from a large amount of past fixes and warnings.
[src:formal-methods/static-program-analysis] For certain types of warnings, it is possible to design and implement automated remediation techniques.
[src:formal-methods/static-program-analysis] For example, Logozzo and Ball have proposed automated remediations for C# *cccheck*.
[src:formal-methods/temporal-logic] In logic, a **temporal logic** is any system of rules and symbolism for representing, and reasoning about, propositions qualified in terms of time (for example, "I am *always* hungry", "I will *eventually* be hungry", or "I will be hungry *until* I eat something").
[src:formal-methods/temporal-logic] Temporal logic has found an important application in formal verification, where it is used to state requirements of hardware or software systems.
[src:formal-methods/temporal-logic] For instance, one may wish to say that *whenever* a request is made, access to a resource is *eventually* granted, but it is *never* granted to two requestors simultaneously.
[src:formal-methods/temporal-logic] Such a statement can conveniently be expressed in a temporal logic.
[src:formal-methods/temporal-logic] The term *temporal logic* is also sometimes used to refer specifically to **tense logic**, a modal logic-based system of temporal logic introduced by Arthur Prior in the late 1950s, with important contributions by Hans Kamp.
[src:formal-methods/temporal-logic] It has been further developed by computer scientists, notably Amir Pnueli, and logicians.
[src:formal-methods/temporal-logic] Though its meaning is constant in time, the statement's truth value can vary in time.
[src:formal-methods/temporal-logic] Sometimes it is true, and sometimes false, but never simultaneously true *and* false.
[src:formal-methods/temporal-logic] In a temporal logic, a statement can have a truth value that varies in time—in contrast with an atemporal logic, which applies only to statements whose truth values are constant in time.
[src:formal-methods/temporal-logic] This treatment of truth-value over time differentiates temporal logic from computational verb logic.
[src:formal-methods/temporal-logic] Temporal logic always has the ability to reason about a timeline.
[src:formal-methods/temporal-logic] So-called "linear-time" logics are restricted to this type of reasoning.
[src:formal-methods/temporal-logic] Branching-time logics, however, can reason about multiple timelines.
[src:formal-methods/temporal-logic] This permits in particular treatment of environments that may act unpredictably.
[src:formal-methods/temporal-logic] To continue the example, in a branching-time logic we may state that "there is a possibility that I will stay hungry forever", and that "there is a possibility that eventually I am no longer hungry".
[src:formal-methods/temporal-logic] If we do not know whether or not I will ever be fed, these statements can both be true.
[src:formal-methods/temporal-logic] Although Aristotle's logic is almost entirely concerned with the theory of the categorical syllogism, there are passages in his work that are now seen as anticipations of temporal logic, and may imply an early, partially developed form of first-order temporal modal bivalent logic.
[src:formal-methods/temporal-logic] The first system of temporal logic was published in 1947 by Polish logician, Jerzy Łoś.
[src:formal-methods/temporal-logic] In his work *Podstawy Analizy Metodologicznej Kanonów Milla* (*The Foundations of a Methodological Analysis of Mill’s Methods*) he presented a formalization of Mill's canons.
[src:formal-methods/temporal-logic] In Łoś's approach, emphasis was placed on the time factor.
[src:formal-methods/temporal-logic] Thus, to reach his goal, he had to create a logic that could provide means for formalization of temporal functions.
[src:formal-methods/temporal-logic] The logic could be seen as a byproduct of Łoś's main aim, albeit it was the first positional logic that, as a framework, was used later for Łoś's inventions in epistemic logic.
[src:formal-methods/temporal-logic] The logic itself has syntax very different than Prior's tense logic, which uses modal operators.
[src:formal-methods/temporal-logic] The language of Łoś's logic rather uses a realization operator, specific to positional logic, which binds the expression with the specific context in which its truth-value is considered.
[src:formal-methods/temporal-logic] In Łoś's work this considered context was only temporal, thus expressions were bound with specific moments or intervals of time.
[src:formal-methods/temporal-logic] Arthur Prior was concerned with the philosophical implications of free will and predestination.
[src:formal-methods/temporal-logic] According to his wife, he first considered formalizing temporal logic in 1953.
[src:formal-methods/temporal-logic] Results of his research were first presented at the conference in Wellington in 1954.
[src:formal-methods/temporal-logic] The system Prior presented, was similar syntactically to Łoś's logic, although not until 1955 did he explicitly refer to Łoś's prior work, in the last section of Appendix 1 in Prior’s *Formal Logic*.
[src:formal-methods/temporal-logic] Along with **tense logic,** Prior constructed a few systems of positional logic, which inherited their main ideas from Łoś.
[src:formal-methods/temporal-logic] Prior gave lectures on the topic at the University of Oxford in 1955–6, and in 1957 published *Time and Modality*, in which he introduced a propositional modal logic with two temporal connectives (modal operators), F and P, corresponding to "sometime in the future" and "sometime in the past".
[src:formal-methods/temporal-logic] In this early work, Prior considered time to be linear.
[src:formal-methods/temporal-logic] In 1958 however, he received a letter from Saul Kripke, who pointed out that this assumption is perhaps unwarranted.
[src:formal-methods/temporal-logic] In a development that foreshadowed a similar one in computer science, Prior took this under advisement, and developed two theories of branching time, which he called "Ockhamist" and "Peircean".
[src:formal-methods/temporal-logic] Between 1958 and 1965 Prior also corresponded with Charles Leonard Hamblin, and a number of early developments in the field can be traced to this correspondence, for example Hamblin implications.
[src:formal-methods/temporal-logic] Prior published his most mature work on the topic, the book *Past, Present, and Future* in 1967.
[src:formal-methods/temporal-logic] Work in positional temporal logics was continued by Nicholas Rescher in the 60s and 70s.
[src:formal-methods/temporal-logic] In such works as *Note on Chronological Logic* (1966), *On the Logic of Chronological Propositions* (1968)*, Topological Logic* (1968), and *Temporal Logic* (1971) he researched connections between Łoś's and Prior's systems.
[src:formal-methods/temporal-logic] Moreover, he proved that Prior's tense operators could be defined using a realization operator in specific positional logics.
[src:formal-methods/temporal-logic] Rescher, in his work, also created more general systems of positional logics.
[src:formal-methods/temporal-logic] Although the first ones were constructed for purely temporal uses, he proposed the term **topological logics** for logics that were meant to contain a realization operator but had no specific temporal axioms—like the clock axiom.
[src:formal-methods/temporal-logic] The binary temporal operators *Since* and *Until* were introduced by Hans Kamp in his 1968 Ph.D. thesis, which also contains an important result relating temporal logic to first-order logic—a result now known as Kamp's theorem.
[src:formal-methods/temporal-logic] Two early contenders in formal verifications were linear temporal logic, a linear-time logic by Amir Pnueli, and computation tree logic (CTL), a branching-time logic by Mordechai Ben-Ari, Zohar Manna and Amir Pnueli.
[src:formal-methods/temporal-logic] An almost equivalent formalism to CTL was suggested around the same time by E.
[src:formal-methods/temporal-logic] The fact that the second logic can be decided more efficiently than the first does not reflect on branching- and linear-time logics in general, as has sometimes been argued.
[src:formal-methods/temporal-logic] Rather, Emerson and Lei show that any linear-time logic can be extended to a branching-time logic that can be decided with the same complexity.
[src:formal-methods/temporal-logic] Łoś’s logic was published as his 1947 master’s thesis *Podstawy Analizy Metodologicznej Kanonów Milla* (*The Foundations of a Methodological Analysis of Mill’s Methods*).
[src:formal-methods/temporal-logic] His philosophical and formal concepts could be seen as continuations of those of the Lviv–Warsaw School of Logic, as his supervisor was Jerzy Słupecki, disciple of Jan Łukasiewicz.
[src:formal-methods/temporal-logic] The paper was not translated into English until 1977, although Henryk Hiż presented in 1951 a brief, but informative, review in the *Journal of Symbolic Logic*.
[src:formal-methods/temporal-logic] This review contained core concepts of Łoś’s work and was enough to popularize his results among the logical community.
[src:formal-methods/temporal-logic] The main aim of this work was to present Mill's canons in the framework of formal logic.
[src:formal-methods/temporal-logic] To achieve this goal the author researched the importance of temporal functions in the structure of Mill's concept.
[src:formal-methods/temporal-logic] Having that, he provided his axiomatic system of logic that would fit as a framework for Mill's canons along with their temporal aspects.
[src:formal-methods/temporal-logic] The sentential tense logic introduced in *Time and Modality* has four (non-truth-functional) modal operators (in addition to all usual truth-functional operators in first-order propositional logic).
[src:formal-methods/temporal-logic] Kripke models are used to evaluate the truth of sentences in TL.
[src:formal-methods/temporal-logic] A pair (*T*, <) of a set *T* and a binary relation < on *T* (called "precedence") is called a **frame**.
[src:formal-methods/temporal-logic] A **model** is given by triple (*T*, <, *V*) of a frame and a function *V* called a **valuation** that assigns to each pair (*a*, *u*) of an atomic formula and a time value some truth value.
[src:formal-methods/temporal-logic] Many sentences are only valid for a limited class of frames.
[src:formal-methods/temporal-logic] It is common to restrict the class of frames to those with a relation < that is transitive, antisymmetric, reflexive, trichotomic, irreflexive, total, dense, or some combination of these.
[src:formal-methods/temporal-logic] **Mirroring**: given a theorem *A*, deduce its **mirror statement** *A*§, which is obtained by replacing G by H (and so F by P) and vice versa.
[src:formal-methods/temporal-logic] **Duality**: given a theorem *A*, deduce its **dual statement** *A**, which is obtained by interchanging ∧ with ∨, G with F, and H with P.
[src:formal-methods/temporal-logic] Burgess gives a *Meredith translation* from statements in TL into statements in first-order logic with one free variable *x*0 (representing the present moment).
[src:formal-methods/temporal-logic] where $A^{+}$ is the sentence A with all variable indices incremented by 1 and $a^{*}$ is a one-place predicate defined by $x\mapsto V(a,x)$ .
[src:formal-methods/temporal-logic] Temporal logic has two kinds of operators: logical operators and modal operators.
[src:formal-methods/temporal-logic] Logical operators are usual truth-functional operators ( $\neg ,\lor ,\land ,\rightarrow$ ).
[src:formal-methods/temporal-logic] The modal operators used in linear temporal logic and computation tree logic are defined as follows.
[src:formal-methods/temporal-logic] Unary operators are well-formed formulas whenever B(*φ*) is well-formed.
[src:formal-methods/temporal-logic] Binary operators are well-formed formulas whenever B(*φ*) and C(*φ*) are well-formed.
[src:formal-methods/temporal-logic] In some logics, some operators cannot be expressed.
[src:formal-methods/temporal-logic] For example, **N** operator cannot be expressed in temporal logic of actions.
[src:formal-methods/temporal-logic] A variation, closely related to temporal or chronological or tense logics, are modal logics based upon "topology", "place", or "spatial position".
[src:formal-methods/tla] For design and documentation, TLA+ fulfills the same purpose as informal technical specifications.
[src:formal-methods/tla] However, TLA+ specifications are written in a formal language of logic and mathematics, and the precision of specifications written in this language is intended to uncover design flaws before system implementation is underway.
[src:formal-methods/tla] Since TLA+ specifications are written in a formal language, they are amenable to finite model checking.
[src:formal-methods/tla] The model checker finds all possible system behaviours up to some number of execution steps, and examines them for violations of desired invariance properties such as safety and liveness.
[src:formal-methods/tla] TLA+ specifications use basic set theory to define safety (bad things won't happen) and temporal logic to define liveness (good things eventually happen).
[src:formal-methods/tla] TLA+ is also used to write machine-checked proofs of correctness both for algorithms and mathematical theorems.
[src:formal-methods/tla] The proofs are written in a declarative, hierarchical style independent of any single theorem prover backend.
[src:formal-methods/tla] Both formal and informal structured mathematical proofs can be written in TLA+; the language is similar to LaTeX, and tools exist to translate TLA+ specifications to LaTeX documents.
[src:formal-methods/tla] TLA+ was introduced in 1999, following several decades of research into a verification method for concurrent systems.
[src:formal-methods/tla] Ever since, a toolchain has been developed, including an IDE and a distributed model checker.
[src:formal-methods/tla] The pseudocode-like language PlusCal was created in 2009; it transpiles to TLA+ and is useful for specifying sequential algorithms.
[src:formal-methods/tla] TLA+2 was announced in 2014, expanding language support for proof constructs.
[src:formal-methods/tla] The current TLA+ reference is The TLA+ Hyperbook by Leslie Lamport.
[src:formal-methods/tla] Modern temporal logic was developed by Arthur Prior in 1957, then called tense logic.
[src:formal-methods/tla] Pnueli researched the use of temporal logic in specifying and reasoning about computer programs, introducing linear temporal logic in 1977.
[src:formal-methods/tla] LTL became an important tool for analysis of concurrent programs, easily expressing properties such as mutual exclusion and freedom from deadlock.
[src:formal-methods/tla] Concurrent with Pnueli's work on LTL, academics were working to generalize Hoare logic for verification of multiprocess programs.
[src:formal-methods/tla] Leslie Lamport became interested in the problem after peer review found an error in a paper he submitted on mutual exclusion.
[src:formal-methods/tla] Ed Ashcroft introduced invariance in his 1975 paper "Proving Assertions About Parallel Programs", which Lamport used to generalize Floyd's method in his 1977 paper "Proving Correctness of Multiprocess Programs".
[src:formal-methods/tla] Lamport's paper also introduced safety and liveness as generalizations of partial correctness and termination, respectively.
[src:formal-methods/tla] This method was used to verify the first concurrent garbage collection algorithm in a 1978 paper with Edsger Dijkstra.
[src:formal-methods/tla] Lamport first encountered Pnueli's LTL during a 1978 seminar at Stanford organized by Susan Owicki.
[src:formal-methods/tla] His search for a practical method of specification resulted in the 1983 paper "Specifying Concurrent Programming Modules", which introduced the idea of describing state transitions as Boolean-valued functions of primed and unprimed variables.
[src:formal-methods/tla] Work continued throughout the 1980s, and Lamport began publishing papers on the temporal logic of actions in 1990; however, it was not formally introduced until "The Temporal Logic of Actions" was published in 1994.
[src:formal-methods/tla] TLA specifications mostly consisted of ordinary non-temporal mathematics, which Lamport found less cumbersome than a purely temporal specification.
[src:formal-methods/tla] TLA provided a mathematical foundation to the specification language TLA+, introduced with the paper "Specifying Concurrent Systems with TLA+" in 1999.
[src:formal-methods/tla] Later that same year, Yuan Yu wrote the TLC model checker for TLA+ specifications; TLC was used to find errors in the cache coherence protocol for a Compaq multiprocessor.
[src:formal-methods/tla] Lamport published a full textbook on TLA+ in 2002, titled "Specifying Systems: The TLA+ Language and Tools for Software Engineers".
[src:formal-methods/tla] PlusCal was introduced in 2009, and the TLA+ proof system (TLAPS) in 2012.
[src:formal-methods/tla] TLA+2 was announced in 2014, adding some additional language constructs as well as greatly increasing in-language support for the proof system.
[src:formal-methods/tla] Lamport is engaged in creating an updated TLA+ reference, "The TLA+ Hyperbook".
[src:formal-methods/tla] The incomplete work is available from his official website.
[src:formal-methods/tla] Lamport is also creating The TLA+ Video Course, described therein as "a work in progress that consists of the beginning of a series of video lectures to teach programmers and software engineers how to write their own TLA+ specifications".
[src:formal-methods/tla] TLA+ specifications are organized into modules.
[src:formal-methods/tla] Modules can extend (import) other modules to use their functionality.
[src:formal-methods/tla] Although the TLA+ standard is specified in typeset mathematical symbols, existing TLA+ tools use LaTeX-like symbol definitions in ASCII.
[src:formal-methods/tla] TLA+ concerns itself with defining the set of all correct system behaviours.
[src:formal-methods/tla] The next-state relation **Tick** sets *clock*′ (the value of *clock* in the next state) to 1 if *clock* is 0, and 0 if *clock* is 1.
[src:formal-methods/tla] The state predicate **Init** is true if the value of *clock* is either 0 or 1.
[src:formal-methods/tla] **Spec** is a temporal formula asserting all behaviours of one-bit clock must initially satisfy **Init** and have all steps either match **Tick** or be stuttering steps.
[src:formal-methods/tla] The safety properties of the one-bit clock – the set of reachable system states – are adequately described by the spec.
[src:formal-methods/tla] The above spec disallows strange states for the one-bit clock, but does not say the clock will ever tick.
[src:formal-methods/tla] A clock which does not tick is not useful, so these behaviours should be disallowed.
[src:formal-methods/tla] One solution is to disable stuttering, but TLA+ requires stuttering always be enabled; a stuttering step represents a change to some part of the system not described in the spec, and is useful for refinement.
[src:formal-methods/tla] Weak fairness over an action means if that action is continuously enabled, it must eventually be taken.
[src:formal-methods/tla] With weak fairness on **Tick** only a finite number of stuttering steps are permitted between ticks.
[src:formal-methods/tla] This temporal logical statement about **Tick** is called a liveness assertion.
[src:formal-methods/tla] In general, a liveness assertion should be *machine-closed*: it shouldn't constrain the set of reachable states, only the set of possible behaviours.
[src:formal-methods/tla] Most specifications do not require assertion of liveness properties.
[src:formal-methods/tla] Safety properties suffice both for model checking and guidance in system implementation.
[src:formal-methods/tla] TLA+ is based on ZF, so operations on variables involve set manipulation.
[src:formal-methods/tla] The language includes set membership, union, intersection, difference, powerset, and subset operators.
[src:formal-methods/tla] First-order logic operators such as ∨, ∧, ¬, ⇒, ↔, ≡ are also included, as well as universal and existential quantifiers ∀ and ∃.
[src:formal-methods/tla] Hilbert's ε is provided as the CHOOSE operator, which uniquely selects an arbitrary set element.
[src:formal-methods/tla] Arithmetic operators over reals, integers, and natural numbers are available from the standard modules.
[src:formal-methods/tla] Temporal logic operators are built into TLA+.
[src:formal-methods/tla] Temporal formulas use $\Box P$ to mean *P* is always true, and $\Diamond P$ to mean *P* is eventually true.
[src:formal-methods/tla] The operators are combined into $\Box \Diamond P$ to mean *P* is true infinitely often, or $\Diamond \Box P$ to mean eventually *P* will always be true.
[src:formal-methods/tla] Other temporal operators include weak and strong fairness.
[src:formal-methods/tla] Weak fairness WFe(*A*) means if action *A* is enabled *continuously* (i.e. without interruptions), it must eventually be taken.
[src:formal-methods/tla] Strong fairness SFe(*A*) means if action *A* is enabled *continually* (repeatedly, with or without interruptions), it must eventually be taken.
[src:formal-methods/tla] Temporal existential and universal quantification are included in TLA+, although without support from the tools.
[src:formal-methods/tla] User-defined operators are similar to macros.
[src:formal-methods/tla] Operators differ from functions in that their domain need not be a set: for example, the set membership operator has the category of sets as its domain, which is not a valid set in ZFC (since its existence leads to Russell's paradox).
[src:formal-methods/tla] Recursive and anonymous user-defined operators were added in TLA+2.
[src:formal-methods/tla] The foundational data structure of TLA+ is the set.
[src:formal-methods/tla] Sets are either explicitly enumerated or constructed from other sets using operators or with `{x \in S : p}` where *p* is some condition on *x*, or `{e : x \in S}` where *e* is some function of *x*.
[src:formal-methods/tla] The unique empty set is represented as `{}`.
[src:formal-methods/tla] Functions in TLA+ assign a value to each element in their domain, a set.
[src:formal-methods/tla] `[S -> T]` is the set of all functions with f[*x*] in *T*, for each *x* in the domain set *S*.
[src:formal-methods/tla] For example, the TLA+ function `Double[x \in Nat] == x*2` is an element of the set `[Nat -> Nat]` so `Double \in [Nat -> Nat]` is a true statement in TLA+.
[src:formal-methods/tla] Functions are also defined with `[x \in S |-> e]` for some expression *e*, or by modifying an existing function `[f EXCEPT ![v1] = v2]`.
[src:formal-methods/tla] The record `[name |-> "John", age |-> 35]` is a record with fields name and age, accessed with `r.name` and `r.age`, and belonging to the set of records `[name : String, age : Nat]`.
[src:formal-methods/tla] They are explicitly defined with `<<e1,e2,e3>>` or constructed with operators from the standard Sequences module.
[src:formal-methods/tla] Sets of tuples are defined by Cartesian product; for example, the set of all pairs of natural numbers is defined `Nat \X Nat`.
[src:formal-methods/tla] TLA+ has a set of standard modules containing common operators.
[src:formal-methods/tla] They are distributed with the syntactic analyzer.
[src:formal-methods/tla] The TLC model checker uses Java implementations for improved performance.
[src:formal-methods/tla] Standard modules are imported with the `EXTENDS` or `INSTANCE` statements.
[src:formal-methods/tla] An integrated development environment is implemented on top of Eclipse.
[src:formal-methods/tla] The IDE is distributed in The TLA Toolbox.
[src:formal-methods/tla] The TLC model checker builds a finite state model of TLA+ specifications for checking invariance properties.
[src:formal-methods/tla] TLC generates a set of initial states satisfying the spec, then performs a breadth-first search over all defined state transitions.
[src:formal-methods/tla] Execution stops when all state transitions lead to states which have already been discovered.
[src:formal-methods/tla] If TLC discovers a state which violates a system invariant, it halts and provides a state trace path to the offending state.
[src:formal-methods/tla] TLC provides a method of declaring model symmetries to defend against combinatorial explosion.
[src:formal-methods/tla] It also parallelizes the state exploration step, and can run in distributed mode to spread the workload across a large number of computers.
[src:formal-methods/tla] As an alternative to exhaustive breadth-first search, TLC can use depth-first search or generate random behaviours.
[src:formal-methods/tla] TLC operates on a subset of TLA+; the model must be finite and enumerable, and some temporal operators are not supported.
[src:formal-methods/tla] In distributed mode TLC cannot check liveness properties, nor check random or depth-first behaviours.
[src:formal-methods/tla] TLC is available as a command line tool or bundled with the TLA toolbox.
[src:formal-methods/tla] The TLA+ Proof System, or TLAPS, mechanically checks proofs written in TLA+.
[src:formal-methods/tla] It was developed at the Microsoft Research-INRIA Joint Centre to prove correctness of concurrent and distributed algorithms.
[src:formal-methods/tla] The proof language is designed to be independent of any particular theorem prover; proofs are written in a declarative style, and transformed into individual obligations which are sent to back-end provers.
[src:formal-methods/tla] The primary back-end provers are Isabelle and Zenon, with fallback to SMT solvers CVC3, Yices, and Z3.
[src:formal-methods/tla] TLAPS proofs are hierarchically structured, easing refactoring and enabling non-linear development: work can begin on later steps before all prior steps are verified, and difficult steps are decomposed into smaller sub-steps.
[src:formal-methods/tla] TLAPS works well with TLC, as the model checker quickly finds small errors before verification is begun.
[src:formal-methods/tla] In turn, TLAPS can prove system properties which are beyond the capabilities of finite model checking.
[src:formal-methods/tla] TLAPS does not currently support reasoning with real numbers, nor most temporal operators.
[src:formal-methods/tla] Isabelle and Zenon generally cannot prove arithmetic proof obligations, requiring use of the SMT solvers.
[src:formal-methods/tla] TLAPS has been used to prove correctness of Byzantine Paxos, the Memoir security architecture, components of the Pastry distributed hash table, and the Spire consensus algorithm.
[src:formal-methods/tla] It is distributed separately from the rest of the TLA+ tools and is free software, distributed under the BSD license.
[src:formal-methods/tla] TLA+2 greatly expanded language support for proof constructs.
[src:formal-methods/tla] At Microsoft, a critical bug was discovered in the Xbox 360 memory module during the process of writing a specification in TLA+.
[src:formal-methods/tla] TLA+ was used to write formal proofs of correctness for Byzantine Paxos and components of the Pastry distributed hash table.
[src:formal-methods/tla] Amazon Web Services has used TLA+ since 2011.
[src:formal-methods/tla] TLA+ model checking uncovered bugs in DynamoDB, S3, EBS, and an internal distributed lock manager; some bugs required state traces of 35 steps.
[src:formal-methods/tla] Model checking was also used to verify aggressive optimizations.
[src:formal-methods/tla] In addition, TLA+ specifications were found to hold value as documentation and design aids.
[src:formal-methods/tla] Microsoft Azure used TLA+ to design Cosmos DB, a globally-distributed database with five different consistency models.
[src:formal-methods/tla] Altreonic NV used TLA+ to model check OpenComRTOS.
